{"title_page": "Darren & Brose", "text_new": "{{Short description|Australian comedian}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n'''Darren & Brose''' are Darren Chau<ref>[http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=80 Screen Producers Association of Australia] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219174607/http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=80 |date=19 February 2012 }}</ref> and Brose Avard, two Australian based [[comedy|comedy writers]] and performers who first met while studying media at [[La Trobe University]]. Chau had been working with the comedy ensemble Chop-Socky,<ref name=\"australiantelevision.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/chop_socky.html|title=Australian Television: Chop-Socky's \u2013 The Prison Of Art|website=www.australiantelevision.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Radio Waves \u2013 Chop-Socky Drive | first = Darrin| last = Farrant | page = | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1998 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/819/theagegreenguidechopsoc.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = A wannabee weekly comedy act goes to air | first = Amanda| last = Hurley| page = | newspaper = [[City Weekly]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1998 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84248452@N02/7713694664/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Chop-Socky| first = |last=| page = | newspaper = [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] Magazine | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1999 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84248452@N02/7713696946/in/photostream/}}</ref> while Avard had been producing and broadcasting on several Melbourne radio stations.<ref>{{cite news | title = Radio Waves \u2013 The Urban Show | first = Darrin| last = Farrant | page = | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1998 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/210/theagegreenguidedarrena.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereo974.com/detailed_news.php?article=80|title=Blog \u2013 Stereo 974|website=Stereo 974}}</ref> They co-founded the Latrobe Media Group and produced comedy shows for the [[Melbourne Fringe Festival]], [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]], [[Channel 31 (Australia)|Channel 31]] and [[Network Ten]]'s [[One (Australian TV channel)|ONE]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Talent scout | first = K | last = Miller | page = | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = December 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://imageshack.com/i/5hzph4j }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Latrobe's inhouse comics take the big stage | first =  | last = | page = 43 | journal = [[Agora]] | year = 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/7/agoramagazine2004saturd.jpg/ }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/darren-and-brose/biography/|title=Darren and Brose|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref>\n\n==Television programs==\nTheir first television project together was the comedy variety program, ''The Rumpus Room with Darren and Brose'',<ref>{{cite news | title = Rumpus Room | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[Inpress]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/651/inpress2002darrenandbro.jpg/}}</ref> which featured sketches, [[music video]] parodies, animations [[animation]]s and special guests<ref name=\"From TV to stage\">{{cite news | title = From TV to stage | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = September 1999 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/850/leadernewspaper1999darr.jpg/}}</ref><ref name=\"Pair loves monkey business\">{{cite news | title = Pair loves monkey business | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2000 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/441/leadernewspaper2000darr.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Students make room for life's big questions | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2000 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84185004@N02/7707703764/in/photostream/}}</ref> including [[Kerry Armstrong]], [[Wil Anderson]], [[Dave Hughes]], [[John Safran]], [[Lawrence Mooney]], [[Dave O'Neil]], [[Jo Stanley]], [[Adam Richard]], [[Damian Callinan]], [[Andrew Gaze]] and [[Santo Cilauro]]. The show concluded after five seasons with an outside broadcast at the [[Melbourne Athenaeum|Athenaeum theatre]] as part of the Melbourne International Comedy Festival.<ref>{{cite news | title = What's the Rumpus? | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[Beat Magazine]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = April 2000 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/33/beatmag2000darrenandbro.jpg/}}</ref><ref name=\"Australian TV Archive\">{{cite web|url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=The%20Rumpus%20Room&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/R&mode=0|title=Australian TV Archive|publisher=|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302220804/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=The%20Rumpus%20Room&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FR&mode=0|archive-date=2 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nChau and Avard were then commissioned by Channel 31 to produce the station's first live nightly program. The nightly one-hour live show ''Darren and Brose''<ref name=\"Australian TV Archive\"/><ref>{{cite news | title = Funny Business| first = Joanne | last = Brookfield | page = | newspaper = [[Beat Magazine]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = September 2002 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/341/beat2002darrenbrosemond.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2404120/|title=Darren and Brose|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> featured special guest interviews, sketches and animations plus regular weekly guests, including Jeff Jenkins, Billy Pinnell, [[Paul McCarthy (Australian actor)|Paul McCarthy]], [[Tony Wilson (Radio Presenter)]], [[Amy Parks]] and Melbourne rock band [[Man Bites God]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FD&mode=0 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302221754/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FD&mode=0 |archive-date=2 March 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The final episode was also their 100th episode in total and featured special guests [[Bert Newton]], [[Tony Martin (comedian)|Tony Martin]], [[Glenn Ridge]], Gavin Wood, [[Stan Zemanek]] and State Minister [[Justin Madden]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Darren and Brose| first = Cameron | last = Burke | page = | newspaper = [[Inpress]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/835/inpress2004saturdaynigh.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/series-final/episode/952998/summary.html?tag=search_results;title;3|title=Darren and Brose: Series Final|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref>\n\nThey returned with the weekly formatted ''Saturday Night Darren and Brose''.<ref>{{cite news | title = Reviving the good old days | first = Monique | last = Bouma | page = 28  | newspaper = [[Manningham Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2004 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84185004@N02/7707704754/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Old Fashioned TV | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[Leader Newspaper]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = April 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/688/leadernewspaper2004satu.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2393264/|title=Saturday Night Darren and Brose|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifitv.com/symbols/5cf278a697f38f73ca4c7367096ac67a.SHOW|title=HugeDomains.com \u2013 Fifitv.com is for sale (Fifitv)|website=fifitv.com}}</ref> Special guests included [[Glenn Robbins]], [[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]], [[Suzie Wilks]]<ref>{{cite news | title = Darren and Brose | first = Simone | last = Ubaldi | page = | newspaper = [[Beat Magazine]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/534/beat2004saturdaynightda.jpg/}}</ref> and [[Tracy Bartram]], along with American comedians [[Kenny Kramer]] and [[Todd Barry]]. When the series ended it was the highest rating programme on Channel 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Saturday%20Night%20Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/S&mode=0|title=Australian TV Archive|publisher=|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302220656/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Saturday%20Night%20Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FS&mode=0|archive-date=2 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/saturday-night-darren-and-brose/|title=Saturday Night Darren and Brose|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the pair re-united to work on ''[[Toon Time (TV series)|Toon Time]]'',<ref>[https://archive.today/20130131120601/http://www.pnop.com/Toon-Time/cast-crew]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.throng.com.au/2011/06/toon-time-featuring-bugs-bunny-to-screen-on-111-hits/|title=Toon Time featuring Bugs Bunny to screen on 111 Hits|date=30 June 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2011/06/111-hits-takes-time-for-toons.html|title=111 HITS takes time for Toons|date=30 June 2011|publisher=}}</ref> which Darren Chau created, co-wrote and executive produced, with Brose Avard writing and producing. The programme was hosted by [[Penelope Mitchell]] and [[Dickie Knee]], became the highest rating local production ever on channel [[111 Hits]], and its promotional campaign won 5 Gold [[Promax Awards]].<ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 11\">{{cite web |title=AWARDS WINNERS 2011 |url=http://www.promaxanz.tv/sites/promaxanz.tantab.com/files/banners/anz11-winnerslist.pdf |website=www.promaxanz.tv |accessdate=30 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111216040639/http://www.promaxanz.tv/sites/promaxanz.tantab.com/files/banners/anz11-winnerslist.pdf |archivedate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 12\">http://www.promaxanz.tv/sites/promaxanz.tantab.com/files/banners/anz12-winners-list.pdf{{dead link|date=October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 it was announced that [[Network Ten]] had picked up a new late night comedy show called [[Darren & Brose (TV series)|Darren & Brose]] to be aired nationally on [[One (Australian TV channel)|ONE]], premiering Thursday 2 July at 11pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/06/darren-brose-to-host-new-late-night-chat-show-for-one.html|title=Darren & Brose to host new late-night chat show for ONE|date=9 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==The 'Lost Tapes'==\nThought not to have been in existence, a box of digital tapes were found with recordings of Darren & Brose's live to air TV shows, including Channel 31's very first ever live, daily show. On 23 May 2013 these tapes began being released weekly on-line via the Darren & Brose web-site and YouTube serving as a time-capsule snapshot of the era, the various faces that appeared as guests and the early work of many people who were trained on these shows and have gone on to have successful careers in the industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/05/video-vault-flashes-back-to-ch-31-show.html|title=Video vault flashes back to Ch 31 show|date=23 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.throng.com.au/2013/05/lost-tapes-reveal-televisions-best-kept-secret/|title=LOST TAPES REVEAL TELEVISION'S BEST KEPT SECRET|date=13 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Brose's solo work==\nBrose Avard has acted in numerous television shows including ''[[Prank Patrol (Australian TV series)|Prank Patrol]]'', ''[[Lowdown (TV series)|Lowdown]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.subs.to/movie-details/2dns8RHon3|title=subs.to \u2013 This website is for sale! \u2013 Subtitles Resources and Information.|website=www.subs.to}}</ref> and ''[[Kath & Kim (Australian TV series)|Kath & Kim]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.screened.com/brose-avard/14-747985/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210101311/http://www.screened.com/brose-avard/14-747985/ |archive-date=10 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemarx.ro/seriale-tv/cu-Brose-Avard-1456093/|title=Seriale TV cu Brose Avard|website=CinemaRx.ro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/kk/series3.html|title=Australian Television: Kath & Kim: episode guide: series 3|website=www.australiantelevision.net}}</ref> In addition, he has starred in several national television campaigns including ''[[Jeep|JEEP]]'' and Matador BBQ.\n\nHe is also a television warm-up performer having worked for every Australian network on shows including ''[[Santo, Sam and Ed's Sports Fever!]]'', ''[[The Project (Australian TV program)|The Project]]'', ''[[The Circle (TV program)|The Circle]]'', ''The Chat Room'', ''[[Millionaire Hot Seat]]'', ''[[Letters and Numbers]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/shows/lettersandnumbers/about/page/i/2/h/The-Show/|title=Letters and Numbers|website=SBS On Demand |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160121071911/http://www.sbs.com.au/shows/lettersandnumbers/about/page/i/2/h/The-Show/ |archive-date=21 January 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Einstein Factor]]'' and ''[[Shaun Micallef's Mad as Hell]]''.\n\nAvard hosts the film discussion podcast Chatflix.\n\n==Darren's solo work==\nDarren Chau was a founding member of the comedy ensemble Chop-Socky, who wrote, performed and produced for ABC's ''[[Recovery (TV series)|Recovery]]'', [[3RRR]] FM, the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] and a scripted comedy produced by [[Artist Services]] for Foxtel, which he wrote, acted in and directed.<ref name=\"australiantelevision.net\"/><ref name=\"From TV to stage\"/><ref name=\"Pair loves monkey business\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chop-Socky's \u2013 The Prison Of Art \u2013 Australian Television Archive |url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Chop-Socky%5E39s%20-%20The%20Prison%20Of%20Art&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/C&mode=0 |website=austv.hostforweb.com |access-date=30 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203203720/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Chop-Socky%5E39s%20-%20The%20Prison%20Of%20Art&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FC&mode=0 |archive-date=3 February 2014 |date=24 February 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/chop-sockys-the-prison-of-art/|title=Chop-Socky's The Prison of Art|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref> He has written and produced hundreds of hours of television and created over a dozen shows including [[Jimeoin: Over the Top]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Jimeoin-Over-Top/dp/B00FKPT76I|title=Jimeoin: Over the Top|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref> The Chaser's War On Everything \u2013 Red Button Edition and [[A Night at the Festival Club]]<ref>{{cite web |title=A Night at the Festival Club |url=https://www.thetvdb.com/series/a-night-at-the-festival-club |website=TVDB |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref>  which evolved into ABC's [[Comedy Up Late]].\n\nHe was a producer, and head writer for ABC's ''[[The Einstein Factor]]'', before accepting the role at Foxtel as group programming director for [[The Comedy Channel]] and [[111 Hits]],<ref>[http://www.communityfoods.org.au/sites/default/files/managed/files/NetworkCommissioningEditor_July2010.pdf]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref> the latter being a brand new entertainment channel he co-created and launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/111-hits-will-target-24-54s.html |title=111 Hits will target 24-54's |access-date=2008-10-20 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022084011/http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/111-hits-will-target-24-54s.html |archive-date=22 October 2008 |df=dmy |date=2008-10-19 }}</ref> The channel launched on Saturday, 1 November 2008 with a special he conceived named ''[[Countdown (Australian TV series)|Countdown to 111 Hits]]'' that featured [[Molly Meldrum]], [[Jenna Elfman]], [[Ian Thorpe]], [[Bonnie Tyler]], [[John Paul Young]], [[The Angels (Australian band)|The Angels]] and [[Jermaine Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/countdown-revives-to-launch-111-hits.html |title=Countdown revives to launch 111 Hits  |last=Knox |first=David |website=TV Tonight |date=24 October 2008 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> The channel was rebranded [[111 Greats]] in 2014. At Foxtel he launched dozens of overseas shows to Australian audiences including ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'', ''[[the Graham Norton Show]]'', ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]'', ''[[Tosh.0]]'', ''[[Russell Howard's Good News]]'' and [[Adult Swim]] titles including ''[[Robot Chicken]]''. He also returned past shows to Australian screens including ''[[Prisoner (TV series)|Prisoner]]'', and in 2013 Foxtel's Brian Walsh publicly thanked and credited Darren Chau for inspiring the idea to create ''[[Wentworth (TV series)|Wentworth]]'', Foxtel's highest rating non-sports program of all time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/05/record-ratings-for-wentworth.html|title=Record ratings for Wentworth|date=21 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref> and winner of the Astra Award for Most Outstanding Drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/03/2014-astra-awards-winners.html|title=2014 ASTRA Awards: winners|date=20 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref> He created, developed and executive produced 30 local productions including ''[[Balls of Steel Australia]]'' which became The Comedy Channel's highest ever rating series\n<ref name=\"ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2011/04/balls-of-steel-australia-tops-comedy-channel.html|title=Balls of Steel Australia tops Comedy Channel|date=20 April 2011|publisher=}}</ref> and won the Astra Award for Most Outstanding Light Entertainment Programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/06/fox-sports-cloudstreet-selling-houses-australia-top-2012-astra-awards.html|title=FOX Sports, Cloudstreet, Selling Houses Australia top 2012 ASTRA Awards.|date=21 June 2012|publisher=}}</ref> Chau led both the Comedy Channel and 111 Hits to record ratings years, also winning fourteen [[Promax Awards]],<ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 11\"/><ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 12\"/> including the World Gold for best entertainment program campaign,<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 PROMAXBDA PROMOTION & MARKETING WORLD GOLD AWARDS WINNERS LIST |url=http://www.intersections.tv/2011/2011-PromaxBDA-PromoMktg-World-Gold-Winners.pdf |website=www.intersections.tv |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224242/http://www.intersections.tv/2011/2011-PromaxBDA-PromoMktg-World-Gold-Winners.pdf |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> and the national television Captioning Award.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 2010 Captioning Awards winners are |url=http://www.mediaaccess.org.au/node/230 |website=Media Access Australia |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309075936/http://www.mediaaccess.org.au/node/230 |archivedate=9 March 2016 |date=27 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Last night's 2010 Captioning Awards was a celebration of all the achievements made in captioning over the last year... |url=http://www.ai-media.tv/news/2010_Captioning_Awards_Night |website=Access Innovation Media |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524062907/http://www.ai-media.tv/news/2010_Captioning_Awards_Night |archivedate=24 May 2014 |date=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe created and produced the development initiative and reality TV format'' [[Comedy Gold (TV series)|Comedy Gold]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Comedy Gold |url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Comedy%20Gold&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/C&mode=0 |website=austv.hostforweb.com |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224534/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Comedy%20Gold&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FC&mode=0 |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which ran for two years, discovering talent such as [[Troy Kinne]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/06/troy-kinne-comedy-coming-to-7mate.html|title=Troy Kinne comedy coming to 7mate|date=11 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> and uncovering programme concepts from talent including [[Jason Gann]], Stephen Kearney ([[Friends]], [[Los Trios Ringbarkus]], [[Garbo (film)]]), Marty Fields and [[The Agony of Life]] series by [[Adam Zwar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/vote-for-comedy-gold.html|title=Vote for Comedy Gold|date=7 October 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://returnon.wordpress.com/tag/comedy/|title=comedy \u2013 re: turn on|website=returnon.wordpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UGC Campaigns \u2013 Profits, Prizes and Pitfalls |url=http://onproductions.com.au/2009/05/15/ugc-mkt-cam/ |website=onproductions.com.au |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304185106/http://onproductions.com.au/2009/05/15/ugc-mkt-cam/ |archivedate=4 March 2015 |date=15 May 2009}}</ref> as well as executive producing the eventual competition winner starring [[Colin Lane]], [[Toby Truslove]], [[Kitty Flanagan]] and [[Patrick Brammall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c21media.net/archives/45284|title=C21Media|website=C21Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.throng.com.au/2009/09/production-begins-on-i-cant-believe-its-not-better/|title=Production Begins On I Can't Believe It's Not Better|date=16 September 2009|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com.au/search?q=darren+chau+comedy+gold&hl=en&gbv=2&prmd=ivnso&ei=a18bUL2pN6W6iQeEk4DoCg&start=20&sa=N|title=darren chau comedy gold \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Production Details \u2013 I Can't Believe It's Not Better |url=http://www.screenhub.com.au/industry/production_detail.php?productionID=1999 |website=Screen Hub |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330074442/http://www.screenhub.com.au/industry/production_detail.php?productionID=1999 |archivedate=30 March 2012}}</ref> He has worked as a consultant for several broadcasters and production companies including making improvements to [[Millionaire Hot Seat]] which saw the programme help the [[Nine Network]] win the 6pm news ratings.\n\nIn 2016 he was appointed director of programming, Discovery Networks Australia and New Zealand, overseeing seven channels including the [[Discovery Channel (Australia)]], [[Animal Planet (Australia and New Zealand)]], [[Discovery Science (Asian TV channel)|Discovery Science]] and [[Discovery Turbo]]. In 2018 he was promoted to head of factual content & brands, managing Discovery's suite of Factual Entertainment channels across ANZ and Pacific Islands, heading up marketing and digital, programming and acquisitions, and production and development, along with executive producing global hits including [[Aussie Gold Hunters]] airing in more than 135 countries and [[Outback Opal Hunters]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aidc.com.au/whos-coming/darren-chau/|title=Darren Chau|publisher=}}</ref> which was nominated for Best Documentary Series at the [[Screen Producers Australia]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/11/screen-producers-awards-2018-winners.html|title=Screen Producers Awards 2018: winners|publisher=}}</ref> In 2020 as Discovery's director of factual content & channels, he co-created and launched the brand new free to air channel [[9Rush]], a joint venture between Discovery, Inc.|Discovery]] and [[Nine Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/9rush-channel-to-launch-with-adrenaline-reality.html|title=9Rush channel to launch with adrenaline reality|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a regular guest speaker at the [[SPAA Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/17gmqtj|title=SPAA CONFERENCE \u2013 Darren Chau \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an%3D1%26subarticlenbr%3D80 |title=Speakers |access-date=2012-02-19 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219174607/http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=80 |archive-date=19 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> is an official judge of the [[International Emmy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/ndjtwfj|title=EMMY JURORS \u2013 Darren Chau, the Comedy Channel & 111 HITS, FOXTEL \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref> and was appointed by the [[International Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] as the expert moderator for the Comedy Nominee Panel session at the Emmy's World Television Festival in New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Schedule |url=http://www.iemmys.tv/files/2010%20Festival%20Program.pdf |website=www.iemmys.tv |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312223742/http://www.iemmys.tv/files/2010%20Festival%20Program.pdf |archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/g4f0z0j|title=Emmy's World Television Festival 2010 Darren Chau \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nAlong with ''[[Radio Karate]]'' ([[Ryan Shelton]] and [[Hamish & Andy]]), Darren & Brose were nominated as finalists for numerous awards including Program of the Year, Best Variety Program, Best Comedy, Best Producer, and Best Presenter at the inaugural [[Antenna Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mctcltd.org.au/antennas/about.html|title=The 2010 National Antenna Awards \u2013 Showcasing Outstanding Achievement in Australian Community Television|website=www.mctcltd.org.au}}</ref>\n\nThe pair beat out thousands of submissions from around Australia to be selected as finalists for [[Network Ten]]'s ELEVEN OUT OF TEN Development Initiative as part the television industry's [[SPAA Conference]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SPAA Conference 2010 |url=http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=264 |website=Screen Producers Association Australia |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013201310/http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=264 |archivedate=13 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/5bw850j|title=ELEVEN OUT OF TEN Pitch Competition \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref>\n\n==Latrobe Media Group==\nDarren & Brose co-founded the Latrobe Media Group which discovered and trained dozens of future international media talent.<ref>{{cite news | title = UniTV show fades to black | first = Heather | last = Ellis | page = 28  | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708710012/in/photostream/}}</ref> The alumni includes German based journalist and presenter Stefanie Suren,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/dw/article/0,,6708459,00.html|title=Stefanie Suren \u2013 DW \u2013 02.02.2012|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref><ref>Stefanie Suren</ref> TV news reporter [[Amy Parks]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Amy Parks |url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=602114 |website=news.ninemsn.com.au |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605171112/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=602114 |archivedate=5 June 2011}}</ref> senior journalist and news presenter Natalie Schenken,<ref>[https://archive.today/20130205003804/http://a0.twimg.com/profile_images/1812542883/image.jpg]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ck_NWfbELE|title=Natalie Schenken NEWSREADER|last=NatalieSchenken|date=5 September 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2012/11/28/sevens-in-strife-unless-meakins-successors-shine-in-2013/?wpmp_switcher=mobile|title=Seven's in strife unless Meakin's successors shine in 2013|date=28 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/11/seven-news-switch-after-pre-recorded-updates-revealed.html|title=Seven News switch after pre-recorded Updates revealed|date=27 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref> Abu Dhabi based Journalist Saeed Saeed,<ref>{{cite news | title = Kicking up a Rumpus makes job sense | first = | last = | page = 28  | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708707520/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Saeed Saeed |url=https://www.thenational.ae/authors/saeed-saeed |website=The National |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071722/https://www.thenational.ae/authors/saeed-saeed |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> German based radio presenter Susanne Henn,<ref>[http://www.dw.de/dw/article/0,2144,1896456,00.html]{{dead link|date=November 2018}}</ref> radio news presenter Miriam Maghrabi,<ref>{{cite web |title=Newsroom |url=http://www.cruise1323.com.au/shows/newsroom/ |website=Cruise 1323 |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321142101/http://www.cruise1323.com.au/shows/newsroom/ |archivedate=21 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Melbourne Cup Highlights \u2013 Videos |url=http://www.mix1011.com.au/videos/melbourne-cup-highlights |website=Mix101.1 |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202181801/http://www.mix1011.com.au/videos/melbourne-cup-highlights |archivedate=2 February 2014 |date=5 November 2012}}</ref> actress and comedian Hayley Butcher,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Megan |title=Review: Dash & D'bree in Take It |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/archive/entertainment/review-dash-dbree-in-take-it/news-story/fdf8878d83034e4cf43b7b8d8b5b8fc4 |website=Herald Sun |accessdate=2 November 2018 |date=4 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bordermail.com.au/story/58658/comedian-is-ready-to-shine|title=Comedian is ready to shine|first=AISHA|last=DOW|date=30 May 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dennehy |first1=Luke |title=Could they be the next Kath & Kim? |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/archive/entertainment/could-they-be-the-next-kath-kim/news-story/344b963fde4d2d4538f452a17c60d5a4 |website=Herald Sun |accessdate=2 November 2018 |date=28 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[Neighbours]]'' writer Shaun Topp, television Editor Rob Buttery,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxcutters.net/2009/02/15/episode169/|title=Ep 169: Editor Rob Buttery, Eleventh Hour, Count Duckula|date=15 February 2009|publisher=}}</ref> television director Richard Franc and television producers Andrea Williams,<ref>{{cite news | title = Rumpus crew romps in | first = Kate | last = Jones | page = | newspaper = [[Preston Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708708328/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Students head for Rumpus Room fun | first = | last = | page = 28  | newspaper = [[Preston Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708709164/in/photostream/}}</ref> Chris Thompson and Adrian Beck.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Channel 31}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darren and Brose}}\n[[Category:Australian comedy duos]]\n[[Category:Australian comedy troupes]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Australian comedian}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n'''Darren & Brose''' are Darren Chau<ref>[http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=80 Screen Producers Association of Australia] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219174607/http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=80 |date=19 February 2012 }}</ref> and Brose Avard, two Australian based [[comedy|comedy writers]] and performers who first met while studying media at [[La Trobe University]]. Chau had been working with the comedy ensemble Chop-Socky,<ref name=\"australiantelevision.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/chop_socky.html|title=Australian Television: Chop-Socky's \u2013 The Prison Of Art|website=www.australiantelevision.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Radio Waves \u2013 Chop-Socky Drive | first = Darrin| last = Farrant | page = | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1998 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/819/theagegreenguidechopsoc.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = A wannabee weekly comedy act goes to air | first = Amanda| last = Hurley| page = | newspaper = [[City Weekly]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1998 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84248452@N02/7713694664/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Chop-Socky| first = |last=| page = | newspaper = [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] Magazine | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1999 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84248452@N02/7713696946/in/photostream/}}</ref> while Avard had been producing and broadcasting on several Melbourne radio stations.<ref>{{cite news | title = Radio Waves \u2013 The Urban Show | first = Darrin| last = Farrant | page = | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | year = 1998 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/210/theagegreenguidedarrena.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereo974.com/detailed_news.php?article=80|title=Blog \u2013 Stereo 974|website=Stereo 974}}</ref> They co-founded the Latrobe Media Group and produced comedy shows for the [[Melbourne Fringe Festival]], [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]], [[Channel 31 (Australia)|Channel 31]] and [[Network Ten]]'s [[One (Australian TV channel)|ONE]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Talent scout | first = K | last = Miller | page = | newspaper = [[The Age]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = December 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://imageshack.com/i/5hzph4j }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Latrobe's inhouse comics take the big stage | first =  | last = | page = 43 | journal = [[Agora]] | year = 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/7/agoramagazine2004saturd.jpg/ }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/darren-and-brose/biography/|title=Darren and Brose|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref>\n\n==Television programs==\nTheir first television project together was the comedy variety program, ''The Rumpus Room with Darren and Brose'',<ref>{{cite news | title = Rumpus Room | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[Inpress]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/651/inpress2002darrenandbro.jpg/}}</ref> which featured sketches, [[music video]] parodies, animations [[animation]]s and special guests<ref name=\"From TV to stage\">{{cite news | title = From TV to stage | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = September 1999 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/850/leadernewspaper1999darr.jpg/}}</ref><ref name=\"Pair loves monkey business\">{{cite news | title = Pair loves monkey business | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2000 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/photo/my-images/441/leadernewspaper2000darr.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Students make room for life's big questions | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2000 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84185004@N02/7707703764/in/photostream/}}</ref> including [[Kerry Armstrong]], [[Wil Anderson]], [[Dave Hughes]], [[John Safran]], [[Lawrence Mooney]], [[Dave O'Neil]], [[Jo Stanley]], [[Adam Richard]], [[Damian Callinan]], [[Andrew Gaze]] and [[Santo Cilauro]]. The show concluded after five seasons with an outside broadcast at the [[Melbourne Athenaeum|Athenaeum theatre]] as part of the Melbourne International Comedy Festival.<ref>{{cite news | title = What's the Rumpus? | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[Beat Magazine]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = April 2000 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/33/beatmag2000darrenandbro.jpg/}}</ref><ref name=\"Australian TV Archive\">{{cite web|url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=The%20Rumpus%20Room&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/R&mode=0|title=Australian TV Archive|publisher=|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302220804/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=The%20Rumpus%20Room&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FR&mode=0|archive-date=2 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nChau and Avard were then commissioned by Channel 31 to produce the station's first live nightly program. The nightly one-hour live show ''Darren and Brose''<ref name=\"Australian TV Archive\"/><ref>{{cite news | title = Funny Business| first = Joanne | last = Brookfield | page = | newspaper = [[Beat Magazine]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = September 2002 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/341/beat2002darrenbrosemond.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2404120/|title=Darren and Brose|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> featured special guest interviews, sketches and animations plus regular weekly guests, including Jeff Jenkins, Billy Pinnell, [[Paul McCarthy (Australian actor)|Paul McCarthy]], [[Tony Wilson (Radio Presenter)]], [[Amy Parks]] and Melbourne rock band [[Man Bites God]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FD&mode=0 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302221754/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FD&mode=0 |archive-date=2 March 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The final episode was also their 100th episode in total and featured special guests [[Bert Newton]], [[Tony Martin (comedian)|Tony Martin]], [[Glenn Ridge]], Gavin Wood, [[Stan Zemanek]] and State Minister [[Justin Madden]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Darren and Brose| first = Cameron | last = Burke | page = | newspaper = [[Inpress]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/835/inpress2004saturdaynigh.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/series-final/episode/952998/summary.html?tag=search_results;title;3|title=Darren and Brose: Series Final|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref>\n\nThey returned with the weekly formatted ''Saturday Night Darren and Brose''.<ref>{{cite news | title = Reviving the good old days | first = Monique | last = Bouma | page = 28  | newspaper = [[Manningham Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2004 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84185004@N02/7707704754/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Old Fashioned TV | first = | last = | page = | newspaper = [[Leader Newspaper]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = April 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/688/leadernewspaper2004satu.jpg/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2393264/|title=Saturday Night Darren and Brose|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifitv.com/symbols/5cf278a697f38f73ca4c7367096ac67a.SHOW|title=HugeDomains.com \u2013 Fifitv.com is for sale (Fifitv)|website=fifitv.com}}</ref> Special guests included [[Glenn Robbins]], [[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]], [[Suzie Wilks]]<ref>{{cite news | title = Darren and Brose | first = Simone | last = Ubaldi | page = | newspaper = [[Beat Magazine]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2004 | accessdate = | url = http://imageshack.us/f/534/beat2004saturdaynightda.jpg/}}</ref> and [[Tracy Bartram]], along with American comedians [[Kenny Kramer]] and [[Todd Barry]]. When the series ended it was the highest rating programme on Channel 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Saturday%20Night%20Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/S&mode=0|title=Australian TV Archive|publisher=|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302220656/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Saturday%20Night%20Darren%20and%20Brose&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FS&mode=0|archive-date=2 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/saturday-night-darren-and-brose/|title=Saturday Night Darren and Brose|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the pair re-united to work on ''[[Toon Time (TV series)|Toon Time]]'',<ref>[https://archive.today/20130131120601/http://www.pnop.com/Toon-Time/cast-crew]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.throng.com.au/2011/06/toon-time-featuring-bugs-bunny-to-screen-on-111-hits/|title=Toon Time featuring Bugs Bunny to screen on 111 Hits|date=30 June 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2011/06/111-hits-takes-time-for-toons.html|title=111 HITS takes time for Toons|date=30 June 2011|publisher=}}</ref> which Darren Chau created, co-wrote and executive produced, with Brose Avard writing and producing. The programme was hosted by [[Penelope Mitchell]] and [[Dickie Knee]], became the highest rating local production ever on channel [[111 Hits]], and its promotional campaign won 5 Gold [[Promax Awards]].<ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 11\">{{cite web |title=AWARDS WINNERS 2011 |url=http://www.promaxanz.tv/sites/promaxanz.tantab.com/files/banners/anz11-winnerslist.pdf |website=www.promaxanz.tv |accessdate=30 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111216040639/http://www.promaxanz.tv/sites/promaxanz.tantab.com/files/banners/anz11-winnerslist.pdf |archivedate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 12\">http://www.promaxanz.tv/sites/promaxanz.tantab.com/files/banners/anz12-winners-list.pdf{{dead link|date=October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 it was announced that [[Network Ten]] had picked up a new late night comedy show called [[Darren & Brose (TV series)|Darren & Brose]] to be aired nationally on [[One (Australian TV channel)|ONE]], premiering Thursday 2 July at 11pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/06/darren-brose-to-host-new-late-night-chat-show-for-one.html|title=Darren & Brose to host new late-night chat show for ONE|date=9 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==The 'Lost Tapes'==\nThought not to have been in existence, a box of digital tapes were found with recordings of Darren & Brose's live to air TV shows, including Channel 31's very first ever live, daily show. On 23 May 2013 these tapes began being released weekly on-line via the Darren & Brose web-site and YouTube serving as a time-capsule snapshot of the era, the various faces that appeared as guests and the early work of many people who were trained on these shows and have gone on to have successful careers in the industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/05/video-vault-flashes-back-to-ch-31-show.html|title=Video vault flashes back to Ch 31 show|date=23 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.throng.com.au/2013/05/lost-tapes-reveal-televisions-best-kept-secret/|title=LOST TAPES REVEAL TELEVISION'S BEST KEPT SECRET|date=13 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Brose's solo work==\nBrose Avard has acted in numerous television shows including ''[[Prank Patrol (Australian TV series)|Prank Patrol]]'', ''[[Lowdown (TV series)|Lowdown]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.subs.to/movie-details/2dns8RHon3|title=subs.to \u2013 This website is for sale! \u2013 Subtitles Resources and Information.|website=www.subs.to}}</ref> and ''[[Kath & Kim (Australian TV series)|Kath & Kim]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.screened.com/brose-avard/14-747985/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210101311/http://www.screened.com/brose-avard/14-747985/ |archive-date=10 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemarx.ro/seriale-tv/cu-Brose-Avard-1456093/|title=Seriale TV cu Brose Avard|website=CinemaRx.ro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/kk/series3.html|title=Australian Television: Kath & Kim: episode guide: series 3|website=www.australiantelevision.net}}</ref> In addition, he has starred in several national television campaigns including ''[[Jeep|JEEP]]'' and Matador BBQ.\n\nHe is also a television warm-up performer having worked for every Australian network on shows including ''[[Santo, Sam and Ed's Sports Fever!]]'', ''[[The Project (Australian TV program)|The Project]]'', ''[[The Circle (TV program)|The Circle]]'', ''The Chat Room'', ''[[Millionaire Hot Seat]]'', ''[[Letters and Numbers]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/shows/lettersandnumbers/about/page/i/2/h/The-Show/|title=Letters and Numbers|website=SBS On Demand |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160121071911/http://www.sbs.com.au/shows/lettersandnumbers/about/page/i/2/h/The-Show/ |archive-date=21 January 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Einstein Factor]]'' and ''[[Shaun Micallef's Mad as Hell]]''.\n\nAvard hosts the film discussion podcast Chatflix.\n\n==Darren's solo work==\nDarren Chau was a founding member of the comedy ensemble Chop-Socky, who wrote, performed and produced for ABC's ''[[Recovery (TV series)|Recovery]]'', [[3RRR]] FM, the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] and a scripted comedy produced by [[Artist Services]] for Foxtel, which he wrote, acted in and directed.<ref name=\"australiantelevision.net\"/><ref name=\"From TV to stage\"/><ref name=\"Pair loves monkey business\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chop-Socky's \u2013 The Prison Of Art \u2013 Australian Television Archive |url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Chop-Socky%5E39s%20-%20The%20Prison%20Of%20Art&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/C&mode=0 |website=austv.hostforweb.com |access-date=30 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203203720/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Chop-Socky%5E39s%20-%20The%20Prison%20Of%20Art&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FC&mode=0 |archive-date=3 February 2014 |date=24 February 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/chop-sockys-the-prison-of-art/|title=Chop-Socky's The Prison of Art|last=TV.com|website=TV.com}}</ref> He has written and produced hundreds of hours of television and created over a dozen shows including [[Jimeoin: Over the Top]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Jimeoin-Over-Top/dp/B00FKPT76I|title=Jimeoin: Over the Top|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref> The Chaser's War On Everything \u2013 Red Button Edition and [[A Night at the Festival Club]]<ref>{{cite web |title=A Night at the Festival Club |url=https://www.thetvdb.com/series/a-night-at-the-festival-club |website=TVDB |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref>  which evolved into ABC's [[Comedy Up Late]].\n\nHe was a producer, and head writer for ABC's ''[[The Einstein Factor]]'', before accepting the role at Foxtel as group programming director for [[The Comedy Channel]] and [[111 Hits]],<ref>[http://www.communityfoods.org.au/sites/default/files/managed/files/NetworkCommissioningEditor_July2010.pdf]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref> the latter being a brand new entertainment channel he co-created and launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/111-hits-will-target-24-54s.html |title=111 Hits will target 24-54's |access-date=2008-10-20 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022084011/http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/111-hits-will-target-24-54s.html |archive-date=22 October 2008 |df=dmy |date=2008-10-19 }}</ref> The channel launched on Saturday, 1 November 2008 with a special he conceived named ''[[Countdown (Australian TV series)|Countdown to 111 Hits]]'' that featured [[Molly Meldrum]], [[Jenna Elfman]], [[Ian Thorpe]], [[Bonnie Tyler]], [[John Paul Young]], [[The Angels (Australian band)|The Angels]] and [[Jermaine Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/countdown-revives-to-launch-111-hits.html |title=Countdown revives to launch 111 Hits  |last=Knox |first=David |website=TV Tonight |date=24 October 2008 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> The channel was rebranded [[111 Greats]] in 2014. At Foxtel he launched dozens of overseas shows to Australian audiences including ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'', ''[[the Graham Norton Show]]'', ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]'', ''[[Tosh.0]]'', ''[[Russell Howard's Good News]]'' and [[Adult Swim]] titles including ''[[Robot Chicken]]''. He also returned past shows to Australian screens including ''[[Prisoner (TV series)|Prisoner]]'', and in 2013 Foxtel's Brian Walsh publicly thanked and credited Darren Chau for inspiring the idea to create ''[[Wentworth (TV series)|Wentworth]]'', Foxtel's highest rating non-sports program of all time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/05/record-ratings-for-wentworth.html|title=Record ratings for Wentworth|date=21 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref> and winner of the Astra Award for Most Outstanding Drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/03/2014-astra-awards-winners.html|title=2014 ASTRA Awards: winners|date=20 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref> He created, developed and executive produced 30 local productions including ''[[Balls of Steel Australia]]'' which became The Comedy Channel's highest ever rating series\n<ref name=\"ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2011/04/balls-of-steel-australia-tops-comedy-channel.html|title=Balls of Steel Australia tops Comedy Channel|date=20 April 2011|publisher=}}</ref> and won the Astra Award for Most Outstanding Light Entertainment Programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/06/fox-sports-cloudstreet-selling-houses-australia-top-2012-astra-awards.html|title=FOX Sports, Cloudstreet, Selling Houses Australia top 2012 ASTRA Awards.|date=21 June 2012|publisher=}}</ref> Chau led both the Comedy Channel and 111 Hits to record ratings years, also winning fourteen [[Promax Awards]],<ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 11\"/><ref name=\"promaxanz.tv 12\"/> including the World Gold for best entertainment program campaign,<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 PROMAXBDA PROMOTION & MARKETING WORLD GOLD AWARDS WINNERS LIST |url=http://www.intersections.tv/2011/2011-PromaxBDA-PromoMktg-World-Gold-Winners.pdf |website=www.intersections.tv |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224242/http://www.intersections.tv/2011/2011-PromaxBDA-PromoMktg-World-Gold-Winners.pdf |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> and the national television Captioning Award.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 2010 Captioning Awards winners are |url=http://www.mediaaccess.org.au/node/230 |website=Media Access Australia |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309075936/http://www.mediaaccess.org.au/node/230 |archivedate=9 March 2016 |date=27 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Last night's 2010 Captioning Awards was a celebration of all the achievements made in captioning over the last year... |url=http://www.ai-media.tv/news/2010_Captioning_Awards_Night |website=Access Innovation Media |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524062907/http://www.ai-media.tv/news/2010_Captioning_Awards_Night |archivedate=24 May 2014 |date=27 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe created and produced the development initiative and reality TV format'' [[Comedy Gold (TV series)|Comedy Gold]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Comedy Gold |url=http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Comedy%20Gold&section=Television%20History%20Reference/TV%20Shows/C&mode=0 |website=austv.hostforweb.com |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224534/http://austv.hostforweb.com/cgi-bin/cgi2/index.rb?page=Comedy%20Gold&section=Television%20History%20Reference%2FTV%20Shows%2FC&mode=0 |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which ran for two years, discovering talent such as [[Troy Kinne]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/06/troy-kinne-comedy-coming-to-7mate.html|title=Troy Kinne comedy coming to 7mate|date=11 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> and uncovering programme concepts from talent including [[Jason Gann]], Stephen Kearney ([[Friends]], [[Los Trios Ringbarkus]], [[Garbo (film)]]), Marty Fields and [[The Agony of Life]] series by [[Adam Zwar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/vote-for-comedy-gold.html|title=Vote for Comedy Gold|date=7 October 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://returnon.wordpress.com/tag/comedy/|title=comedy \u2013 re: turn on|website=returnon.wordpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UGC Campaigns \u2013 Profits, Prizes and Pitfalls |url=http://onproductions.com.au/2009/05/15/ugc-mkt-cam/ |website=onproductions.com.au |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304185106/http://onproductions.com.au/2009/05/15/ugc-mkt-cam/ |archivedate=4 March 2015 |date=15 May 2009}}</ref> as well as executive producing the eventual competition winner starring [[Colin Lane]], [[Toby Truslove]], [[Kitty Flanagan]] and [[Patrick Brammall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c21media.net/archives/45284|title=C21Media|website=C21Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.throng.com.au/2009/09/production-begins-on-i-cant-believe-its-not-better/|title=Production Begins On I Can't Believe It's Not Better|date=16 September 2009|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com.au/search?q=darren+chau+comedy+gold&hl=en&gbv=2&prmd=ivnso&ei=a18bUL2pN6W6iQeEk4DoCg&start=20&sa=N|title=darren chau comedy gold \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Production Details \u2013 I Can't Believe It's Not Better |url=http://www.screenhub.com.au/industry/production_detail.php?productionID=1999 |website=Screen Hub |accessdate=31 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330074442/http://www.screenhub.com.au/industry/production_detail.php?productionID=1999 |archivedate=30 March 2012}}</ref> He has worked as a consultant for several broadcasters and production companies including making improvements to [[Millionaire Hot Seat]] which saw the programme help the [[Nine Network]] win the 6pm news ratings.\n\nIn 2016 he was appointed director of programming, Discovery Networks Australia and New Zealand, overseeing seven channels including the [[Discovery Channel (Australia)]], [[Animal Planet (Australia and New Zealand)]], [[Discovery Science (Asian TV channel)|Discovery Science]] and [[Discovery Turbo]]. In 2018 he was promoted to Head of Factual Content & Brands, managing Discovery\u2019s suite of Factual Entertainment channels across ANZ and Pacific Islands, heading up marketing and digital, programming and acquisitions, and production and development, along with executive producing global hits including [[Aussie Gold Hunters]] airing in more than 135 countries and [[Outback Opal Hunters]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aidc.com.au/whos-coming/darren-chau/|title=Darren Chau|publisher=}}</ref> which was nominated for Best Documentary Series at the [[Screen Producers Australia]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/11/screen-producers-awards-2018-winners.html|title=Screen Producers Awards 2018: winners|publisher=}}</ref> In 2020 as Discovery's director of factual content & channels, he co-created and launched the brand new free to air channel [[9Rush]], a joint venture between Discovery, Inc.|Discovery]] and [[Nine Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/9rush-channel-to-launch-with-adrenaline-reality.html|title=9Rush channel to launch with adrenaline reality|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a regular guest speaker at the [[SPAA Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/17gmqtj|title=SPAA CONFERENCE \u2013 Darren Chau \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an%3D1%26subarticlenbr%3D80 |title=Speakers |access-date=2012-02-19 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219174607/http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=80 |archive-date=19 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> is an official judge of the [[International Emmy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/ndjtwfj|title=EMMY JURORS \u2013 Darren Chau, the Comedy Channel & 111 HITS, FOXTEL \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref> and was appointed by the [[International Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] as the expert moderator for the Comedy Nominee Panel session at the Emmy's World Television Festival in New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Schedule |url=http://www.iemmys.tv/files/2010%20Festival%20Program.pdf |website=www.iemmys.tv |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312223742/http://www.iemmys.tv/files/2010%20Festival%20Program.pdf |archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/g4f0z0j|title=Emmy's World Television Festival 2010 Darren Chau \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nAlong with ''[[Radio Karate]]'' ([[Ryan Shelton]] and [[Hamish & Andy]]), Darren & Brose were nominated as finalists for numerous awards including Program of the Year, Best Variety Program, Best Comedy, Best Producer, and Best Presenter at the inaugural [[Antenna Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mctcltd.org.au/antennas/about.html|title=The 2010 National Antenna Awards \u2013 Showcasing Outstanding Achievement in Australian Community Television|website=www.mctcltd.org.au}}</ref>\n\nThe pair beat out thousands of submissions from around Australia to be selected as finalists for [[Network Ten]]'s ELEVEN OUT OF TEN Development Initiative as part the television industry's [[SPAA Conference]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SPAA Conference 2010 |url=http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=264 |website=Screen Producers Association Australia |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013201310/http://conference.spaa.org.au/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=264 |archivedate=13 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://imageshack.com/i/5bw850j|title=ELEVEN OUT OF TEN Pitch Competition \u2013 Click to see more photos|website=ImageShack}}</ref>\n\n==Latrobe Media Group==\nDarren & Brose co-founded the Latrobe Media Group which discovered and trained dozens of future international media talent.<ref>{{cite news | title = UniTV show fades to black | first = Heather | last = Ellis | page = 28  | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708710012/in/photostream/}}</ref> The alumni includes German based journalist and presenter Stefanie Suren,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/dw/article/0,,6708459,00.html|title=Stefanie Suren \u2013 DW \u2013 02.02.2012|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref><ref>Stefanie Suren</ref> TV news reporter [[Amy Parks]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Amy Parks |url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=602114 |website=news.ninemsn.com.au |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605171112/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=602114 |archivedate=5 June 2011}}</ref> senior journalist and news presenter Natalie Schenken,<ref>[https://archive.today/20130205003804/http://a0.twimg.com/profile_images/1812542883/image.jpg]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ck_NWfbELE|title=Natalie Schenken NEWSREADER|last=NatalieSchenken|date=5 September 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2012/11/28/sevens-in-strife-unless-meakins-successors-shine-in-2013/?wpmp_switcher=mobile|title=Seven's in strife unless Meakin's successors shine in 2013|date=28 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/11/seven-news-switch-after-pre-recorded-updates-revealed.html|title=Seven News switch after pre-recorded Updates revealed|date=27 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref> Abu Dhabi based Journalist Saeed Saeed,<ref>{{cite news | title = Kicking up a Rumpus makes job sense | first = | last = | page = 28  | newspaper = [[The Leader (Melbourne)|The Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708707520/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Saeed Saeed |url=https://www.thenational.ae/authors/saeed-saeed |website=The National |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071722/https://www.thenational.ae/authors/saeed-saeed |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> German based radio presenter Susanne Henn,<ref>[http://www.dw.de/dw/article/0,2144,1896456,00.html]{{dead link|date=November 2018}}</ref> radio news presenter Miriam Maghrabi,<ref>{{cite web |title=Newsroom |url=http://www.cruise1323.com.au/shows/newsroom/ |website=Cruise 1323 |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321142101/http://www.cruise1323.com.au/shows/newsroom/ |archivedate=21 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Melbourne Cup Highlights \u2013 Videos |url=http://www.mix1011.com.au/videos/melbourne-cup-highlights |website=Mix101.1 |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202181801/http://www.mix1011.com.au/videos/melbourne-cup-highlights |archivedate=2 February 2014 |date=5 November 2012}}</ref> actress and comedian Hayley Butcher,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Megan |title=Review: Dash & D'bree in Take It |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/archive/entertainment/review-dash-dbree-in-take-it/news-story/fdf8878d83034e4cf43b7b8d8b5b8fc4 |website=Herald Sun |accessdate=2 November 2018 |date=4 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bordermail.com.au/story/58658/comedian-is-ready-to-shine|title=Comedian is ready to shine|first=AISHA|last=DOW|date=30 May 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dennehy |first1=Luke |title=Could they be the next Kath & Kim? |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/archive/entertainment/could-they-be-the-next-kath-kim/news-story/344b963fde4d2d4538f452a17c60d5a4 |website=Herald Sun |accessdate=2 November 2018 |date=28 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[Neighbours]]'' writer Shaun Topp, television Editor Rob Buttery,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxcutters.net/2009/02/15/episode169/|title=Ep 169: Editor Rob Buttery, Eleventh Hour, Count Duckula|date=15 February 2009|publisher=}}</ref> television director Richard Franc and television producers Andrea Williams,<ref>{{cite news | title = Rumpus crew romps in | first = Kate | last = Jones | page = | newspaper = [[Preston Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708708328/in/photostream/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Students head for Rumpus Room fun | first = | last = | page = 28  | newspaper = [[Preston Leader]] | publisher = | location = Melbourne | date = March 2002 | accessdate = | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/84181908@N05/7708709164/in/photostream/}}</ref> Chris Thompson and Adrian Beck.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Channel 31}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darren and Brose}}\n[[Category:Australian comedy duos]]\n[[Category:Australian comedy troupes]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darren_%26_Brose"}
{"title_page": "Long Gone (film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Long Gone\n| image                = Long Gone Movie.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = DVD Cover\n| genre                = Comedy<br />Drama<br />Romance<br />Sports\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = ''Long Gone''<br />by [[Paul Hemphill]]\n| writer               = \n| screenplay           = [[Michael Norell]]\n| story                = \n| director             = [[Martin Davidson]]\n| starring             = [[William Petersen]]<br />[[Virginia Madsen]]<br />[[Dermot Mulroney]]<br />[[Larry Riley (actor)|Larry Riley]]<br />[[Katy Boyer]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Phillip Namanworth<br />[[Kenny Vance]]\n| country              = \n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = Joan Barnett\n| editor               = [[Gib Jaffe]]\n| cinematography       = [[Robert Elswit]]\n| runtime              = 113 minutes\n| company              = [[HBO Pictures]]\n| distributor          = [[HBO]]<br>[[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = HBO\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = May 23, 1987\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Long Gone''''' is a 1987 baseball film by [[HBO]] that is based on [[Paul Hemphill]]'s 1979 book of the same name.<ref name=Hemphill>Hemphill, Paul (1979). [https://books.google.com/books?id=Sm4hAQAAIAAJ&q ''Long Gone'']. Published by Viking Press, New York. {{OCLC|4774813}}. {{ISBN|978-0-670-43788-7}}.</ref> The [[television film]] was directed by [[Martin Davidson]] and starred [[William Petersen]], [[Virginia Madsen]], and [[Dermot Mulroney]].<ref name=Ultimate>Didinger, Ray and Macnow, Glen (2009, pp. 190 & 191). [https://books.google.com/books?id=iNReCd-bVlMC&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Ultimate Book of Sports Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Sports Films'']. Published by Running Press, Philadelphia. {{OCLC|316825645}}. {{ISBN|978-0-7624-3548-7}}.</ref> Historic [[McKechnie Field]], located in [[Bradenton, Florida]], was the location for many of the film's scenes. Outside North America, the film was released as ''Stogies''.\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe Tampico [[Stogies]] are a last-place baseball team based in Tampico, Florida.<ref name=Hemphill/> The team competes in the lowest-level (Class D) professional [[Alabama\u2013Florida League|Gulf Coast league]] during the summer of 1957. It is unclear if the team is affiliated with a [[Major League Baseball|major league franchise]]; if so, it receives minimal, if any, support in money or players from the parent club.\n\nThe Stogies are owned by a pair of corrupt and scheming local Tampico businessmen, Hale Buchman (Henry Gibson) and his son, Hale Buchman Jr. (Teller).<ref name=Creamer/> They refer to themselves as [[Business magnate|sports moguls]], despite the team being heavily mortgaged.\n\nTheir star [[player-manager|player and manager]] is an aging Cecil \"Stud\" Cantrell (William Petersen), a hard-drinking, hard-playing, and hard-loving man's man.<ref name=Creamer/> Signed out of high school by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Cantrell was a onetime [[rookie]] standout in the organization, coming up in the same group as [[Stan Musial]], but he never made it to the big leagues because of a [[Wounded in action|war injury]] he sustained in World War II during the [[Guadalcanal Campaign|Battle of Guadalcanal]].<ref name=Ultimate/>\n\nAt a game against the Crestview Cats in [[Alabama]], Cantrell meets a beautiful young woman just voted Miss Strawberry Blossom of 1957, Dixie Lee Boxx (Virginia Madsen)<ref name=John>O'Connor, John (May 22, 1987). [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/22/arts/tv-weekend-long-gone-a-baseball-comedy.html TV Weekend; 'Long Gone,' A Baseball Comedy], ''The New York Times''. Retrieved June 30, 2011.</ref> , botching the lyrics of the [[Star-Spangled Banner]], but still wowing the crowd in her skimpy skin-tight outfit. What Cantrell initially intends to be a [[Casual sex#One-night stand|one-night stand]]  soon develops into a semi-serious [[Intimate relationship|relationship]].<ref name=Creamer/>\n\nCantrell signs a slick-fielding but light-hitting [[second base]]man named Jamie Weeks (Dermot Mulroney). Weeks soon falls for a virginal and church-going local girl, Esther Wrenn (Katy Boyer), who is looking to escape Tampico.<ref name=John/> Cantrell also signs a [[Slugging percentage|power-hitting]], strong-armed [[catcher]], Joe Brown (Larry Riley), who is African American. Because this is the [[Deep South]] during the 1950s, to keep local bigots and [[Ku Klux Klan]] off his back, Cantrell lies that Brown is a [[Venezuela]]n named Jos\u00e9 Luis Brown who can't speak any English.<ref name=Creamer/><ref name=John/>\n\nWith the addition of these new players, the Stogies go on a red-hot [[Winning streak (sports)|winning streak]]. On the verge of a [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]], however, Cantrell is told that throwing the big game would give a substantial boost to his sagging career.<ref name=John/> He is offered a [[Manager (baseball)|managerial]] position in the [[Minor League Baseball|minor leagues]] with the Cardinals organization, on the condition he does not show up for the final game. If he plays, his future managerial career is over.<ref name=Ultimate/>\n\nBrown, poverty-stricken since childhood, is also bribed not to play (with the promise of a fancy car). The team's owners, the Buchmans, are involved in the [[match-fixing]] as well. They set up a trivial yet undeniable scandal in which Cantrell could be implicated in betting on his team's games (for $1.00 per game), giving them leverage by which they can threaten to have him suspended for life.\n\nWhile the pennant-deciding game is being played at Tampico, Cantrell and Brown meet at a local bar where they discuss their moral and ethical dilemmas. Brown erupts in anger, smashing his new car with his baseball bat.\n\nThey elect to hurry to the park and play, much to the anger and regret of the owners. Brown instructs the PA announcer to introduce him by his actual name, Joe Louis Brown.\n\n==Cast==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[William Petersen]] as Cecil \"Stud\" Cantrell\n* [[Virginia Madsen]] as Dixie Lee Boxx\n* [[Dermot Mulroney]] as Jamie Weeks\n* [[Katy Boyer]] as Esther Caroline Wrenn\n* [[Larry Riley (actor)|Larry Riley]] as Joe Louis Brown (aka Jos\u00e9 Brown)\n* [[Henry Gibson]] as Hale Buchman\n* [[Teller (magician)|Teller]] as Hale Buchman Jr. (aka Junior)\n* [[Robert Easton (actor)|Robert Easton]] as Cletis Ramey\n* [[Joel Murray]] as Bart Polanski\n* [[Panchito G\u00f3mez]] as Paco Izquierdo\n* [[David Smyrl|David Langston Smyrl]] as Monroe Wright \n* Guich Koock as Bump Klein\n* Arthur Rosenburg as Peaches Cluff\n* Will Zahrn as Knucksie Chappell\n* Edward Blatchford as Whiz Whsonant\n* Steve Zurk as Buster Smerglia\n* Kenneth Eriksen as Bubba Bean\n* Neil DeGroot as Pukey Smathers\n* Ken Dominguez as Corky Lucadello\n* Mike McKown as Scooter Cagle\n* [[Nardi Contreras]] as Hose Harrigan\n* John Bauldrey as Tommy Tatum\n* Ken Krannick as Rook Robb\n* Kathryn Hasty as Bonnie\n* Tracy Roberts as \"Redhead\"\n* Hazen Gifford as J. Harrell Smythe\n* William Wohrman as Whitey Connerly (Dothan manager)\n* Tony Vila Jr. as Dusty Hoolihan\n* Jim Rabe as Rusty Ledbetter (Dothan pitcher \u2013 championship game)\n* Ronn Allen as Mr. Wrenn\n* Monica Moran as Mrs. Wrenn\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n\nReleased in 1987 by HBO, ''Long Gone'' is a little-known and difficult-to-obtain film that has consequently made it somewhat of a sports [[cult film]]. It has been described as \"three parts ''[[Bull Durham]]'', two parts [[Slap Shot (film)|''Slap Shot'']], add a dose of [[The Bingo Long Traveling All-Stars & Motor Kings|''Bingo Long'']] and a pinch of [[The Longest Yard (1974 film)|''The Longest Yard'']]\".<ref name=Ultimate/> It has also been described as the best baseball movie most of you never saw.<ref name=Jones>Jones, Joseph (March 28, 2011). [http://bleacherreport.com/articles/647819-hbos-long-gone-the-best-baseball-movie-most-of-you-never-saw HBO's \"Long Gone\", The Best Baseball Movie Most of You Never Saw]. ''Bleacher Report''. Retrieved June 30, 2011.</ref>\n\nA book, ''The Baseball Filmography, 1915 Through 2001'', described ''Long Gone'' as one of the most thoroughly enjoyable baseball comedies made in the last two decades.<ref>Erickson, Hal (2002, p. 294). [https://books.google.com/books?id=HuBkAAAAMAAJ&q ''The baseball filmography, 1915 through 2001'']. Published by McFarland, N.C. {{OCLC|49225316}}. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-1272-3}}.</ref> Robert Creamer, a writer for ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', wrote that it was probably the best made-for-television movie he had ever seen.<ref name=Creamer>Creamer, Robert (June 1, 1987). [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1066034/index.htm Low Minors, High Style]. ''SI Vault''. Retrieved June 30, 2011.</ref>\n\nJohn O'Connor, a writer for ''[[The New York Times]]'', wrote that ''Long Gone'' makes classics such as ''[[The Pride of the Yankees]]'' look like promotional fantasies.<ref name=John/> The ''Bleacher Report'' wrote that this film deserves to be included in anyone's collection of baseball features.<ref name=Jones/> ''[[Newsday]]'' called it one of the best sports movies ever made.<ref>Holston, Noel (June 25, 2005). [http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/fanfare/holston-10-1.635983 Holston 10]. ''Newsday''. Retrieved July 5, 2011.</ref> ''Long Gone'' was ranked 50th in ''The Ultimate Book of Sports Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Sports Films''.<ref name=Ultimate/> It also rated a mention in another book, ''The Great Baseball Films'', which stated ''Long Gone'' was an above-average comedy-drama that is full of bite, grit, and good feelings.<ref>Edelman, Rob (1994, p. 111). [https://books.google.com/books?id=MPwHAQAAMAAJ&q ''The great baseball films: from right off the bat to a league of their own'']. Published by Carol Pub, N.J. {{OCLC|29467483}}. {{ISBN|978-0-8065-1479-6}}.</ref>\n\nDespite the positive reviews, ''Long Gone'' has been largely overlooked by [[mainstream media]] and remains extremely difficult to buy on DVD.<ref name=Ultimate/><ref name=Jones/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* Director [[Martin Davidson]] won an [[CableACE Awards|ACE Award]] for the film under the category, Writing award for Biography.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0093433|Long Gone}}\n* [http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/long_gone/ ''Long Gone''] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n* {{tcmdb title|453749|Long Gone}}\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Long-Gone-VHS-William-Petersen/dp/6301648838 ''Long Gone''] at [[Amazon.com|Amazon]]\n\n{{Martin Davidson}}\n\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1987 television films]]\n[[Category:1980s sports films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Davidson]]\n[[Category:Films set in Florida]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Florida]]\n[[Category:HBO Films films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Long Gone\n| image                = Long Gone Movie.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = DVD Cover\n| genre                = Comedy<br />Drama<br />Romance<br />Sports\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = ''Long Gone''<br />by [[Paul Hemphill]]\n| writer               = \n| screenplay           = [[Michael Norell]]\n| story                = \n| director             = [[Martin Davidson]]\n| starring             = [[William Petersen]]<br />[[Virginia Madsen]]<br />[[Dermot Mulroney]]<br />[[Larry Riley (actor)|Larry Riley]]<br />[[Katy Boyer]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Phillip Namanworth<br />[[Kenny Vance]]\n| country              = \n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = Joan Barnett\n| editor               = [[Gib Jaffe]]\n| cinematography       = [[Robert Elswit]]\n| runtime              = 113 minutes\n| company              = [[HBO Pictures]]\n| distributor          = [[HBO]]<br>[[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = HBO\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = May 23, 1987\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Long Gone''''' is a 1987 baseball film by [[HBO]] that is based on [[Paul Hemphill]]'s 1979 book of the same name.<ref name=Hemphill>Hemphill, Paul (1979). [https://books.google.com/books?id=Sm4hAQAAIAAJ&q ''Long Gone'']. Published by Viking Press, New York. {{OCLC|4774813}}. {{ISBN|978-0-670-43788-7}}.</ref> The [[television film]] was directed by [[Martin Davidson]] and starred [[William Petersen]], [[Virginia Madsen]], and [[Dermot Mulroney]].<ref name=Ultimate>Didinger, Ray and Macnow, Glen (2009, pp. 190 & 191). [https://books.google.com/books?id=iNReCd-bVlMC&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Ultimate Book of Sports Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Sports Films'']. Published by Running Press, Philadelphia. {{OCLC|316825645}}. {{ISBN|978-0-7624-3548-7}}.</ref> Historic [[McKechnie Field]], located in [[Bradenton, Florida]], was the location for many of the film's scenes. Outside North America, the film was released as ''Stogies''.\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe Tampico [[Stogies]] are a last-place baseball team based in Tampico, Florida.<ref name=Hemphill/> The team competes in the lowest-level (Class D) professional [[Alabama\u2013Florida League|Gulf Coast league]] during the summer of 1957. It is unclear if the team is affiliated with a [[Major League Baseball|major league franchise]]; if so, it receives minimal, if any, support in money or players from the parent club.\n\nThe Stogies are owned by a pair of corrupt and scheming local Tampico businessmen, Hale Buchman (Henry Gibson) and his son, Hale Buchman Jr. (Teller).<ref name=Creamer/> They refer to themselves as [[Business magnate|sports moguls]], despite the team being heavily mortgaged.\n\nTheir star [[player-manager|player and manager]] is an aging Cecil \"Stud\" Cantrell (William Petersen), a hard-drinking, hard-playing, and hard-loving man's man.<ref name=Creamer/> Signed out of high school by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Cantrell was a onetime [[rookie]] standout in the organization, coming up in the same group as [[Stan Musial]], but he never made it to the big leagues because of a [[Wounded in action|war injury]] he sustained in World War II during the [[Guadalcanal Campaign|Battle of Guadalcanal]].<ref name=Ultimate/>\n\nAt a game against the Crestview Cats in [[Alabama]], Cantrell meets a beautiful young woman just voted Miss Strawberry Blossom of 1957, Dixie Lee Boxx (Virginia Madsen)<ref name=John>O'Connor, John (May 22, 1987). [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/22/arts/tv-weekend-long-gone-a-baseball-comedy.html TV Weekend; 'Long Gone,' A Baseball Comedy], ''The New York Times''. Retrieved June 30, 2011.</ref> , botching the lyrics of the [[Star-Spangled Banner]], but still wowing the crowd in her skimpy skin-tight outfit. What Cantrell initially intends to be a [[Casual sex#One-night stand|one-night stand]]  soon develops into a semi-serious [[Intimate relationship|relationship]].<ref name=Creamer/>\n\nCantrell signs a slick-fielding but light-hitting [[second base]]man named Jamie Weeks (Dermot Mulroney). Weeks soon falls for a virginal and church-going local girl, Esther Wrenn (Katy Boyer), who is looking to escape Tampico.<ref name=John/> Cantrell also signs a [[Slugging percentage|power-hitting]], strong-armed [[catcher]], Joe Brown (Larry Riley), who is African American. Because this is the [[Deep South]] during the 1950s, to keep local bigots and [[Ku Klux Klan]] off his back, Cantrell lies that Brown is a [[Venezuela]]n named Jos\u00e9 Luis Brown who can't speak any English.<ref name=Creamer/><ref name=John/>\n\nWith the addition of these new players, the Stogies go on a red-hot [[Winning streak (sports)|winning streak]]. On the verge of a [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]], however, Cantrell is told that throwing the big game would give a substantial boost to his sagging career.<ref name=John/> He is offered a [[Manager (baseball)|managerial]] position in the [[Minor League Baseball|minor leagues]] with the Cardinals organization, on the condition he does not show up for the final game. If he plays, his future managerial career is over.<ref name=Ultimate/>\n\nBrown, poverty-stricken since childhood, is also bribed not to play (with the promise of a fancy car). The team's owners, the Buchmans, are involved in the [[match-fixing]] as well. They set up a trivial yet undeniable scandal in which Cantrell could be implicated in betting on his team's games (for $1.00 per game), giving them leverage by which they can threaten to have him suspended for life.\n\nWhile the pennant-deciding game is being played at Tampico, Cantrell and Brown meet at a local bar where they discuss their moral and ethical dilemmas. Brown erupts in anger, smashing his new car with his baseball bat.\n\nThey elect to hurry to the park and play, much to the anger and regret of the owners. Brown instructs the PA announcer to introduce him by his actual name, Joe Louis Brown.\n\n==Cast==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[William Petersen]] as Cecil \"Stud\" Cantrell\n* [[Virginia Madsen]] as Dixie Lee Boxx\n* [[Dermot Mulroney]] as Jamie Weeks\n* [[Katy Boyer]] as Esther Caroline Wrenn\n* [[Larry Riley (actor)|Larry Riley]] as Joe Louis Brown (aka Jos\u00e9 Brown)\n* [[Henry Gibson]] as Hale Buchman\n* [[Teller (magician)|Teller]] as Hale Buchman Jr. (aka Junior)\n* [[Robert Easton (actor)|Robert Easton]] as Cletis Ramey\n* [[Joel Murray]] as Bart Polanski\n* [[Panchito G\u00f3mez]] as Paco Izquierdo\n* [[David Smyrl|David Langston Smyrl]] as Monroe Wright \n* Guich Koock as Bump Klein\n* Arthur Rosenburg as Peaches Cluff\n* Will Zahrn as Knucksie Chappell\n* Edward Blatchford as Whiz Whsonant\n* Steve Zurk as Buster Smerglia\n* Kenneth Eriksen as Bubba Bean\n* Neil DeGroot as Pukey Smathers\n* Ken Dominguez as Corky Lucadello\n* Mike McKown as Scooter Cagle\n* [[Nardi Contreras]] as Hose Harrigan\n* John Bauldrey as Tommy Tatum\n* Ken Krannick as Rook Robb\n* Kathryn Hasty as Bonnie\n* Tracy Roberts as \"Redhead\"\n* Hazen Gifford as J. Harrell Smythe\n* William Wohrman as Whitey Connerly (Dothan manager)\n* Tony Vila Jr. as Dusty Hoolihan\n* Jim Rabe as Rusty Ledbetter (Dothan pitcher \u2013 championship game)\n* Ronn Allen as Mr. Wrenn\n* Monica Moran as Mrs. Wrenn\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n\nReleased in 1987 by HBO, ''Long Gone'' is a little-known and difficult-to-obtain film that has consequently made it somewhat of a sports [[cult movie]]. It has been described as \"three parts ''[[Bull Durham]]'', two parts [[Slap Shot (film)|''Slap Shot'']], add a dose of [[The Bingo Long Traveling All-Stars & Motor Kings|''Bingo Long'']] and a pinch of [[The Longest Yard (1974 film)|''The Longest Yard'']]\".<ref name=Ultimate/> It has also been described as the best baseball movie most of you never saw.<ref name=Jones>Jones, Joseph (March 28, 2011). [http://bleacherreport.com/articles/647819-hbos-long-gone-the-best-baseball-movie-most-of-you-never-saw HBO's \"Long Gone\", The Best Baseball Movie Most of You Never Saw]. ''Bleacher Report''. Retrieved June 30, 2011.</ref>\n\nA book, ''The Baseball Filmography, 1915 Through 2001'', described ''Long Gone'' as one of the most thoroughly enjoyable baseball comedies made in the last two decades.<ref>Erickson, Hal (2002, p. 294). [https://books.google.com/books?id=HuBkAAAAMAAJ&q ''The baseball filmography, 1915 through 2001'']. Published by McFarland, N.C. {{OCLC|49225316}}. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-1272-3}}.</ref> Robert Creamer, a writer for ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', wrote that it was probably the best made-for-television movie he had ever seen.<ref name=Creamer>Creamer, Robert (June 1, 1987). [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1066034/index.htm Low Minors, High Style]. ''SI Vault''. Retrieved June 30, 2011.</ref>\n\nJohn O'Connor, a writer for ''[[The New York Times]]'', wrote that ''Long Gone'' makes classics such as ''[[The Pride of the Yankees]]'' look like promotional fantasies.<ref name=John/> The ''Bleacher Report'' wrote that this film deserves to be included in anyone's collection of baseball features.<ref name=Jones/> ''[[Newsday]]'' called it one of the best sports movies ever made.<ref>Holston, Noel (June 25, 2005). [http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/fanfare/holston-10-1.635983 Holston 10]. ''Newsday''. Retrieved July 5, 2011.</ref> ''Long Gone'' was ranked 50th in ''The Ultimate Book of Sports Movies: Featuring the 100 Greatest Sports Films''.<ref name=Ultimate/> It also rated a mention in another book, ''The Great Baseball Films'', which stated ''Long Gone'' was an above-average comedy-drama that is full of bite, grit, and good feelings.<ref>Edelman, Rob (1994, p. 111). [https://books.google.com/books?id=MPwHAQAAMAAJ&q ''The great baseball films: from right off the bat to a league of their own'']. Published by Carol Pub, N.J. {{OCLC|29467483}}. {{ISBN|978-0-8065-1479-6}}.</ref>\n\nDespite the positive reviews, ''Long Gone'' has been largely overlooked by [[mainstream media]] and remains extremely difficult to buy on DVD.<ref name=Ultimate/><ref name=Jones/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* Director [[Martin Davidson]] won an [[CableACE Awards|ACE Award]] for the film under the category, Writing award for Biography.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0093433|Long Gone}}\n* [http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/long_gone/ ''Long Gone''] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n* {{tcmdb title|453749|Long Gone}}\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Long-Gone-VHS-William-Petersen/dp/6301648838 ''Long Gone''] at [[Amazon.com|Amazon]]\n\n{{Martin Davidson}}\n\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1987 television films]]\n[[Category:1980s sports films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Davidson]]\n[[Category:Films set in Florida]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Florida]]\n[[Category:HBO Films films]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Gone_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Baltimore\u2013Washington International Airport", "text_new": "{{redirect|BWI Marshall Airport|the Baltimore Light Rail station|BWI Marshall Airport station|the Amtrak and MARC station|BWI Rail Station}}\n{{short description|airport near Baltimore, Maryland, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name           = Baltimore/Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport\n| image          = BWI Logo.svg\n| image-width    = 150\n| image2         = BWI airport terminal.jpg\n| image2-width   = 250\n| IATA           = BWI\n| ICAO           = KBWI\n| FAA            = BWI\n| WMO            = 72406\n| type           = Public\n| owner          = [[Maryland Aviation Administration]] ([[Maryland Department of Transportation|MDOT]] MAA)\n| operator       = MDOT MAA<ref name=\"mdotMAA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bwiairport.com/flying-with-us/about-bwi/about-mdot-maa|title=About MDOT MAA|website=BWIairport.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 16, 2019|quote=The Maryland Department of Transportation Maryland Aviation Administration (MDOT MAA) is the owner and operator of BWI Marshall Airport (BWI) and Martin State Airport (KMTN).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206140156/https://www.bwiairport.com/flying-with-us/about-bwi/about-mdot-maa|archive-date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| city-served    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Baltimore metropolitan area]]\n* [[Washington metropolitan area]]}}\n* [[Harrisburg-York-Lebanon, PA Combined Statistical Area|Southern Pennsylvania]]\n\n| hub            = [[Southern Airways Express]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transportation.wvu.edu/news-and-announcements/2017/06/15/southern-airways-moves-d-c-area-hub-to-bwi|title=Southern Airways Moves D.C. Area Hub to BWI|publisher=Transportation.WVU.edu|language=en-US|access-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807072526/http://transportation.wvu.edu/news-and-announcements/2017/06/15/southern-airways-moves-d-c-area-hub-to-bwi|archive-date=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| focus_city     = [[Southwest Airlines]], [[Spirit Airlines]]\n| location       = [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland]], U.S.\n| elevation-f    = 143\n| elevation-m    = 44\n| coordinates    = {{coord|39|10|31|N|076|40|06|W|region:US-MD|display=inline,title}}\n| website        = {{URL|https://www.bwiairport.com/|BWIairport.com}}\n| pushpin_map    = USA Maryland#USA\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_label  = '''BWI'''\n| r1-number      = 10/28\n| r1-length-f    = 10,503\n| r1-length-m    = 3,201\n| r1-surface     = Asphalt\n| r2-number      = 15L/33R\n| r2-length-f    = 5,000\n| r2-length-m    = 1,524\n| r2-surface     = Asphalt\n| r3-number      = 15R/33L\n| r3-length-f    = 9,501\n| r3-length-m    = 2,896\n| r3-surface     = Asphalt\n| h1-number      = H1\n| h1-length-f    = 100\n| h1-length-m    = 30\n| h1-surface     = Asphalt\n| stat-year      = 2019\n| stat1-header   = Passengers\n| stat1-data     = 26,993,896\n| stat2-header   = Aircraft operations\n| stat2-data     = 262,597\n| stat3-header   = Cargo\n| stat3-data     = {{convert|500,342,980|lbs|t|0|abbr=on}}\n| footnotes      = Sources: BWI Airport<ref>{{cite web|title=BWI Airport December 2015 Statistics|url=http://www.bwiairport.com/files/assets/stats/Dec2015.pdf|date=December 2015|website=BWIairport.com|access-date=February 10, 2016|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215231529/http://www.bwiairport.com/files/assets/stats/Dec2015.pdf|archive-date=February 15, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Baltimore/Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport''' {{Airport codes|BWI|KBWI|BWI}} is an international airport in the eastern [[United States]]. It serves [[Baltimore, Maryland]], and with [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] and [[Washington National Airport|Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]] is one of three major airports serving the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area|Baltimore\u2013Washington D.C. metropolitan area]]. Located in an unincorporated area of [[Anne Arundel County]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=16000US2447125&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on|title=Linthicum CDP, Maryland|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=March 3, 2010|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606043150/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/MapItDrawServlet?geo_id=16000US2447125&_bucket_id=50&tree_id=420&context=saff&_lang=en&_sse=on|archive-date=June 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> the airport is 9 miles (14&nbsp;km) south of downtown Baltimore and {{convert|30|miles|km}} northeast of [[Washington D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airnav.com/airport/KBWI|title=KBWI Baltimore/Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport Baltimore, Maryland, USA|publisher=AirNav.com|accessdate=October 28, 2016|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026021543/http://www.airnav.com/airport/KBWI|archive-date=October 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwiairport.com/en/travel/maps-and-direction/from/washington|title=Driving Directions: Washington DC|publisher=BWIairport.com|access-date=December 16, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715051323/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/travel/maps-and-direction/from/washington|archive-date=July 15, 2017|url-status=dead|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIt is the busiest airport in Maryland, and the busiest airport in the Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/preliminary-cy2017-commercial-service-enplanements.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128010723/https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/preliminary-cy2017-commercial-service-enplanements.pdf |archive-date=November 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is commonly referred to as '''BWI''' or '''BWI Marshall'''. The airport is named after [[Thurgood Marshall]], a Baltimore native. Thurgood Marshall was the first [[African American]] to serve as a [[justice]] on the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]]. This airport also draws large numbers of travelers from the [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]] and [[Philadelphia]] metropolitan areas. BWI covers 3,160 acres (1,279 ha) of land.<ref name=FAA>{{FAA-airport|ID=BWI|use=PU|own=PU|site=08778.*A}}. Retrieved October 12, 2010.</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early years===\n[[File:BWI Overhead.jpg|thumb|Aerial of BWI Marshall Airport with [[Downtown Baltimore]] in background]]\n[[File:KBWI FAA Airport Diagram.svg|thumb|FAA diagram]]\nPlanning for a new airport on {{convert|3200|acre}} to serve the Baltimore/Washington area began just before the end of [[World War II]]. In 1944, the Baltimore Aviation Commission announced its decision that the best location to build a new airport would be on a {{convert|2100|acre|adj=on}} tract of land near [[Linthicum Heights]].<ref>\"[http://search.proquest.com/docview/151674708/ Arundel Tract Favored For Baltimore Airport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002318/http://search.proquest.com/docview/151674708/ |date=March 5, 2017 }}\". ''The Washington Post.'' August 11, 1944. p. 7.</ref><ref name= anne>\"Anne Arundel Airport Site is Favored: Bonnell Cites Advantages Of 2,100 Acres Near Linthicum Heights\". ''The Baltimore Sun''. August 10, 1944. p. 22.</ref> The cost of building the airport was estimated at $9&nbsp;million.<ref name= anne/> The site was chosen because it was a 15-minute drive from downtown Baltimore; close to the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] line, the [[Baltimore and Annapolis Railroad]] line, and the proposed [[Baltimore\u2013Washington Parkway]]; and visibility was generally good.<ref name= anne/> An alternate site along [[Ritchie Highway|Gov. Ritchie Highway]] at [[Glen Burnie, Maryland|Furnace Branch]] was rejected by the [[United States War Department]], and another possible site at [[Pasadena, Maryland|Lipin's Corner]] was deemed too far from Baltimore.<ref name= anne/> The State Aviation Commission approved of the Linthicum Heights site in 1946.<ref>\"[http://search.proquest.com/docview/151827918/ Linthicum Heights Airport Approved] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002315/http://search.proquest.com/docview/151827918/ |date=March 5, 2017 }}\". ''The Washington Post''. March 17, 1946. p. M3</ref>\n\nMuch of the land was purchased from Friendship Methodist Church in 1946,<ref>{{cite news |title= 500 Acres Acquired For Baltimore Airport |work= The Washington Post |date= June 27, 1946 |page= 3 |url= http://search.proquest.com/docview/151792190/ |access-date= December 22, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002321/http://search.proquest.com/docview/151792190/ |archive-date= March 5, 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> and ground was broken on May 2, 1947.<ref>\"Airport Work Begins Today: City And State Officials To Witness Ground-Breaking\". ''The Baltimore Sun''. May 2, 1947. p. 7.</ref><ref>[http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline/#1949 \"BWI History at a Glance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208051146/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline |date=December 8, 2009 }} BWI Airport Timeline: 1784\u20131947, retrieved December 27, 2011.</ref> Friendship Methodist Church held its last service on Easter Sunday in 1948.<ref name= church>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-02-16/news/1996047047_1_friendship-cemetery-cemetery-board-cemetery-is-closed|title=Work crews unearth potter's field at BWI|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=February 16, 1996|first=Consella A.|last=Lee|access-date=April 19, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222020951/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-02-16/news/1996047047_1_friendship-cemetery-cemetery-board-cemetery-is-closed|archive-date=February 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Friendship Methodist Church was razed to make room for the new airport.<ref name= church/> In addition, several pieces of land were bought,<ref>\"Airport Farm Value Listed At $14,000 By City Appraiser\". ''The Baltimore Sun''. January 7, 1947. p. 6.</ref> and 170 bodies buried in a cemetery were moved.<ref>\"City to Move 170 Bodies: Will Pay To Transfer Those Buried On Airport Site\". ''The Baltimore Sun''. September 27, 1946. p. 19.</ref> [[Maryland Route 170|Baltimore-Fort Meade Road]] was moved to the west to make way for the airport's construction.<ref>\"City Will Pay for Road Shift: Meade Highway Runs Through Projected New Airport\". ''The Baltimore Sun''. October 6, 1946. p. 18.</ref>\n\n'''Friendship International Airport''' was dedicated on June 24, 1950, by U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]]. Truman arrived in the then official presidential plane [[Air Force One|Independence]] from nearby [[Washington National Airport]] carrying the [[Governor of Maryland]], [[William Preston Lane Jr.]], and Baltimore mayor [[Thomas D'Alesandro Jr.]] on his first aircraft flight.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Washington Post|title=Cooperation Built Airport, Truman Says: President Dedicates Baltimore Project; Praises Aid Programs Truman Lauds Cooperation|date=June 25, 1950}}</ref> The total cost to construct the airport totaled $15&nbsp;million.<ref name= airportopen/> The following month the airlines moved to the new airport from the old [[Baltimore Municipal Airport]] (Harbor Field in southeast Baltimore at {{coord|39.25|-76.53|display=inline}}). [[Eastern Airlines]] flew the first scheduled flight, a [[DC-3]], into the airport at 12:01 am on July 23, 1950.<ref name= airportopen>\"Friendship Airport Opens\". ''The Washington Post''. July 24, 1950. p. 12.</ref> Seven minutes later, the same plane was also the first flight to depart from the airport.<ref name= airportopen/> 300 people came to watch the first flight arrive and depart.<ref name= airportopen/>\n\nThe Official Airline Guide for April 1957 shows 52 weekday departures: 19 [[Eastern Air Lines|Eastern]], 12 [[Capital Airlines (United States)|Capital]], 8 [[American Airlines|American]], 4 [[National Airlines (1934\u20131980)|National]], 3 [[Trans World Airlines|TWA]], 3 [[United Airlines|United]], 2 [[Delta Air Lines|Delta]], and 1 [[Allegheny Airlines|Allegheny]]. Miami had a couple of nonstop flights, but westward nonstop flights did not reach beyond Ohio; Baltimore's reach expanded when jet service started. The early Boeing 707s and Douglas DC-8s could not use [[Washington National Airport]] and [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] did not open until 1962, so Baltimore became Washington's jet airport in May\u2013June 1959 when American and TWA began transcontinental 707 flights.<ref>[http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline/#1959 \"BWI History at a Glance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208051146/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline |date=December 8, 2009 }} BWI Airport Timeline: 1950\u201359, retrieved November 16, 2009</ref>\n\n===1970s\u20131990s===\nThe [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] purchased Friendship International Airport from the City of Baltimore for $36 million in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|title=Friendship International Airport from the City of Baltimore for $36 million in 1972|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 8, 1984|author=John Mintz}}</ref> Under MDOT, the [[Maryland State Aviation Administration]] took over airfield operations and grew from three employees to more than 200. Plans to upgrade, improve, and modernize all Maryland airport facilities were announced almost immediately by the Secretary of Transportation, [[Harry Hughes]].\n\nTo attract passengers from the [[Washington metropolitan area]], particularly [[Montgomery County, Maryland|Montgomery]] and [[Prince George's County|Prince George's]] counties,<ref name= newname>\"[http://search.proquest.com/docview/148324405/ New Name for Airport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002318/http://search.proquest.com/docview/148324405/ |date=March 5, 2017 }}\". ''The Washington Post''. October 2, 1973. p. A7.</ref> the airport was renamed '''Baltimore/Washington International Airport''', effective November 16, 1973.<ref name=\"Timeline1979\"/> Its [[IATA airport code|IATA code]], originally BAL, didn't reflect its new name for seven years until the [[International Air Transport Association]] assigned BWI to the airport on April 20, 1980, with the change becoming official six months later on October 26. The BWI code had previously been used by an airport in Bewani, [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1980/04/21/shift-to-bwi-ends-identity-problem-for-md-airport/34c38cb9-c675-4c83-a359-1d8dd79b08c5/ \"Shift to 'BWI' Ends Identity Problem for Md. Airport,\" ''The Washington Post'', Monday, April 21, 1980.] Retrieved February 2, 2020</ref>\n\nThe first phase of the airport's modernization was completed in 1974 at a cost of $30 million. Upgrades included improved instrument landing capabilities and runway systems, and construction of three new air cargo terminals, expanding the airport's freight capacity to {{convert|2.53|acre}}.<ref name=\"Timeline1979\"/>\n\nThe terminal renovation program was complete in 1979, the most dramatic work of the airport's modernization, which was designed by [[AECOM|DMJM]] along with Peterson & Brickbauer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charlesbrickbauer.com/|title=Projects: BWI Airport|publisher=Charles Brickbauer, Architect|accessdate=October 25, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128225135/http://charlesbrickbauer.com/|archive-date=November 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The BWI terminal more than doubled in size to {{convert|14.58|acre|ha}}; the number of gate positions increased from 20 to 27. The total cost was $70 million. To continue the work, the BWI Development Council was established to support initiatives for airport development.<ref name=\"Timeline1979\">[http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline/#1979 \"BWI History at a Glance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208051146/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline |date=December 8, 2009 }} BWI Airport Timeline: 1970\u201379, retrieved November 17, 2009</ref>\n\nThe [[BWI Rail Station]] opened in 1980, providing a connection for passengers on the [[Northeast Corridor]] through [[Amtrak]]. BWI was the first airport in the U.S. with a dedicated intercity rail station.<ref>[http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline/#1989 \"BWI History at a Glance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208051146/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline |date=December 8, 2009 }} BWI Airport Timeline: 1980\u201389, retrieved November 17, 2009</ref> In particular, the station provided rail transit access to Washington, D.C., something that Dulles will not have until 2020 at the earliest.  In 1997 a new international terminal (Concourse E), designed by STV Group and William Nicholas Bodouva & Associates,<ref>{{cite news|title=Designer Chosen for $100 Million BWI Expansion STV Group, Partner Would Design Larger International Wing|first=Edward|last=Gunts|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1992-06-16/business/1992168181_1_stv-group-design-state-officials|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=June 16, 1992|accessdate=June 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407075802/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1992-06-16/business/1992168181_1_stv-group-design-state-officials|archive-date=April 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> was added,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline|title=BWI Timeline: 1990 to 1999|work=BWI History at a Glance|publisher=Maryland Aviation Administration|accessdate=December 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328005535/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline|archivedate=March 28, 2010}}</ref> though Dulles continues to hold the lion's share of the region's international flights, and BWI has not attracted many long-haul international carriers. The first transatlantic nonstops were on World Airways about 1981; [[British Airways]] arrived at BWI a few years later. [[Aer Lingus]],<ref>\"Aer Lingus Launches 'Quick Trips'\". ''Irish Voice'' (New York). November 25, 2003. p. 8.</ref> [[Air Jamaica]],<ref>Shifrin, Carole. \"Jamaica Banks on New Air Service From Baltimore\". ''The Washington Post''. January 25, 1982. p. 30.</ref> [[Air Aruba]],<ref>Curcio, Barbara. \"Worldwise\". ''The Washington Post''. October 31, 1993. p. E03.\n\n</ref> [[Air Greenland]], [[El Al]], [[Ghana Airways]], [[Icelandair]], [[KLM]], Air Canada [[Ladeco]], and [[Mexicana de Aviaci\u00f3n|Mexicana]] previously flew to BWI. Military flights, operated by the [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force's]] [[Air Mobility Command]], continue to have a significant presence at BWI.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\nIn the first half of the 1990s runway 15L/33R was extended {{convert|1,800|ft|m}} from {{convert|3,199|ft|m|abbr=on}} to its current length of {{convert|5,000|ft|m|abbr=on}}, allowing it to be used by small passenger jets like the [[Boeing 737]].\n\nBeginning in the 1980s and for much of the 1990s BWI was a hub for [[Piedmont Airlines (1948\u20131989)|Piedmont Airlines]] and successor [[US Airways#1980s: Mergers and expansion|US Airways]], but that airline's financial problems in the wake of the [[Dot-com bubble|dot-com bust]], the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|September 11 attacks]], and low fare competition forced it to cut back. The airport has been a haven for [[low-cost carrier|low-cost]] flights in the Baltimore/Washington Metropolitan Area since [[Southwest Airlines]]' arrival in September 1993<ref name=\"ACRP Report 76\">{{cite book|title=Addressing Uncertainty about Future Airport Activity Levels in Airport Decision Making|author=Transportation Research Board|year=2012|publisher=National Academy of Sciences|isbn=978-0-309-25857-9|page=90|url=http://onlinepubs.trb.org/onlinepubs/acrp/acrp_rpt_076.pdf|access-date=October 25, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203204156/http://onlinepubs.trb.org/onlinepubs/acrp/acrp_rpt_076.pdf|archive-date=February 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and subsequent expansion in the early 2000s. Southwest is the airport's largest carrier, accounting for 56.12% of passengers carried in 2011.<ref name=\"figures\">[http://www.aci-na.org/stats/stats_traffic 2008 North American Final Rankings] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208130330/http://www.aci-na.org/stats/stats_traffic |date=February 8, 2008 }}. Airports Council International, retrieved February 17, 2010.</ref> [[Southwest Airlines]] currently serves on average 245 daily departures to the US, Mexico and the Caribbean.\n\n===2000s\u2013present===\n[[File:Southwest tails at BWI.jpg|thumb|[[Southwest Airlines]] planes at Concourses A-B]]\nTo accommodate Southwest's extensive presence at the airport, in 2005 Concourses A and B were expanded, renovated, and integrated with one another to house all of that airline's operations there. This new facility, designed by [[URS Corporation]], opened on May 22, 2005. On October 1 of that year, the airport was renamed again, becoming '''Baltimore-Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport,''' to honor former [[Supreme Court of the United States|US Supreme Court]] [[judge|justice]] [[Thurgood Marshall]], who grew up in Baltimore.<ref name=\"Timeline 2005\">[http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline/#2000 \"BWI History at a Glance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208051146/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/bwi-timeline |date=December 8, 2009 }} BWI Airport Timeline: 2005, retrieved November 17, 2009</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://mlis.state.md.us/2005rs/chapters/Ch_442_HB0189E.pdf|title=An Act concerning Baltimore-Washington International Airport and Other State Facilities, Roads, and Bridges \u2013 Naming FOR the purpose of renaming the Baltimore-Washington International Airport as the Baltimore-Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport|access-date=November 20, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110415150015/http://mlis.state.md.us/2005rs/chapters/Ch_442_HB0189E.pdf|archive-date=April 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, 2014 little-used runway 04-22 was permanently closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2010-12-13/features/bs-md-airport-runways-20101209_1_bwi-plans-runway-project-paul-wiedefeld|title=BWI to close main runways for paving|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923103135/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2010-12-13/features/bs-md-airport-runways-20101209_1_bwi-plans-runway-project-paul-wiedefeld|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>  It was 6,000 feet (1,829 meters) long and used primarily when the main runways needed to be closed for repairs. The last operation on the runway was a Southwest Airlines flight from Chicago Midway that arrived at 4:18&nbsp;AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/1135|title=Runway 4-22 Permanently Closed at BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport - BWI Airport - Baltimore Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport|website=www.bwiairport.com|access-date=October 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028170416/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/1135|archive-date=October 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe airport has been a backdrop in numerous films, including ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]'', ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'', ''[[Broadcast News (film)|Broadcast News]]'', ''[[Home for the Holidays (1995 film)|Home for the Holidays]]'' and ''[[12 Monkeys (film)|Twelve Monkeys]]''.\n\nIn late 2008 ''[[Health (magazine)|Health]]'' magazine named BWI the second healthiest airport in the United States.<ref>Formichelli, Linda. \"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/HEALTH/12/16/hm.healthy.airports/index.html Magazine picks America's healthiest airports] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216212607/http://www.cnn.com/2008/HEALTH/12/16/hm.healthy.airports/index.html |date=December 16, 2008 }}.\" ''[[CNN]]''. Wednesday December 17, 2008. Retrieved on October 21, 2009.</ref> In 2009 the airport had a six percent increase in air travelers due to the proliferation of discount flights.<ref>Walker, Andrea K. \"[https://archive.today/20120718115202/http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bal-bz.bwi21oct21,0,2597232.story BWI gains altitude].\" ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''. October 21, 2009. Retrieved on October 21, 2009.</ref> In a 2009 survey of airport service quality by Airports Council International, BWI was the world's top ranking airport in the 15-to-25-million-passenger category.<ref name=\"2009ASQRankings\">[http://www.aci.aero/cda/aci_common/display/main/aci_content07_banners.jsp?zn=aci&cp=1-7-46^35015_725_2__ \"ACI Airport Service Quality Awards 2009\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815184205/http://www.aci.aero/cda/aci_common/display/main/aci_content07_banners.jsp?zn=aci&cp=1-7-46%5E35015_725_2__ |date=August 15, 2012 }} Airports Council International, retrieved February 17, 2010</ref> BWI also ranked seventh, in medium-sized airports, based on customer satisfaction conducted by J.D Power and Associates.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local-beat/BWI-Thurgood-Marshall-International-Airport-Ranks-High-in-Customer-Service-84771047.html|title=BWI Airport Ranks High in Customer Service|author=Elaine Reyes|work=NBC Washington|date=February 19, 2010|accessdate=December 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2016 a partnership between the airport and  [[Towson University]]'s [[WTMD]] Radio Station announced a new concert series that will take place at the terminal's baggage claim on the lower level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/midnight-sun-blog/bal-jenn-wasner-bwi-airport-wtmd-partnership-story.html|title=Jenn Wasner, other Baltimore musicians to perform at BWI Airport|first=Wesley|last=Case|publisher=|access-date=February 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204015547/http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/midnight-sun-blog/bal-jenn-wasner-bwi-airport-wtmd-partnership-story.html|archive-date=February 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The local bands of [[Wye Oak (band)|Wye Oak]], Arboretum, and Super City. This new series follows the release event of [[Animal Collective]]'s new album ''[[Painting With]]'' on November 25, 2015, where the new album was streamed throughout the airport.\n\nIn late 2018 construction began on a $60 Million, 5 gate expansion of terminal A for Southwest.<ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-md-bwi-expansion-vote-20180719-story.html</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n===Terminal===\n[[Image:Kbwi.jpg|thumb|International terminal (Pier E)]]\nBaltimore/Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport has five concourses with 70 total gates and 4 arrival only gates, though Concourses A and B were essentially merged into a single concourse in the renovations completed in 2005, a merging section joining Concourse C with Concourses A/B was completed in 2013, and then Concourse D was merged with Concourse E in the renovations completed in 2017.<ref name=\"Timeline 2005\" /> The [[Maryland Aviation Administration]] has its headquarters on the third floor of the terminal building.<ref>\"[http://www.marylandaviation.com/content/contactmaa/index.html Maryland Aviation Administration Contacts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630083241/http://www.marylandaviation.com/content/contactmaa/index.html |date=June 30, 2010 }}.\" [[Maryland Aviation Administration]]. Retrieved on March 2, 2010.</ref> The airports international gates are located in Concourse E.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baltimore-airport.com/terminal.php |title=BWI Airport Terminal |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''Concourses A and B''' have 25 gates\n*'''Concourse C''' has 14 gates. \n*'''Concourse D''' has 24 gates.\n*'''Concourse E''' has 7 gates.\n\nThe [[United Service Organizations|USO]] operates a lounge on the lower level of the Terminal between the Concourses D and E baggage claim for [[United States military]] personnel and their families. A lounge called The Club is located near Gate D10 and is accessible to [[Priority Pass]] members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2016/05/12/first-airspace-lounge-location-at-bwi-set-to-close.html|title=BWI lounge to close, be replaced|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301092810/http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2016/05/12/first-airspace-lounge-location-at-bwi-set-to-close.html|archive-date=March 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-club-bwi-20170503-story.html|title=New passenger lounge opens at BWI|last=|first=|date=|website=www.baltimoresun.com|access-date=2017-05-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421084201/https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-club-bwi-20170503-story.html|archive-date=April 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[British Airways]] contracts the Chesapeake Club Lounge in Concourse E, near entrance to the concourse, for use by its elite and Club World passengers.\n\n===Cargo===\nThe airport's cargo concourse covers a {{convert|395000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} area. Its facilities include a {{convert|60000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} cargo building in the Midfield Cargo Complex, a [[Foreign trade zones of the United States|foreign trade zone]], a {{convert|17|acre}} air cargo ramp, and ramp parking for 17 aircraft with direct nose-in access for 8 freighters.\n\n===Ground transportation===\n[[File:Baltimore light rail at BWI.agr.jpg|thumb|[[Baltimore Light Rail|Light rail]] train at BWI station]]\nBWI is located at the southeast terminus of [[Interstate 195 (Maryland)|Interstate 195]], a spur route providing connections to the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington Parkway]] and [[Interstate 95 in Maryland|Interstate 95]].\n\nBWI was ranked one of the \"Top 10 Easiest U.S. Airports to Get to\" by [[Imaginova|Aviation.com]] in 2007 and has a light rail station located in its main terminal.<ref>[http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/164 BWI listed in Top 10 of \"easiest airports to get to\" by Aviation.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103031035/http://bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/164 |date=January 3, 2010 }} BWI press release: August 15, 2007. Retrieved November 17, 2009.</ref>\n\nPassenger van service to and from the [[Eastern Shore of Maryland|Eastern Shore]] and [[Western Maryland]] is available through ''[http://www.bayrunnershuttle.com BayRunner Shuttle]'' with services to and from BWI to [[Kent Island, Maryland|Kent Island]], [[Easton, Maryland|Easton]], [[Cambridge, Maryland|Cambridge]], [[Salisbury, Maryland|Salisbury]], [[Ocean Pines, Maryland|Ocean Pines]], and [[Ocean City, Maryland|Ocean City]] (for the [[Eastern Shore of Maryland|Eastern Shore]]) and [[Grantsville, Maryland|Grantsville]], [[Frostburg, Maryland|Frostburg]], [[Cumberland, Maryland|Cumberland]], [[Hancock, Maryland|Hancock]], [[Hagerstown, Maryland|Hagerstown]], and [[Frederick, Maryland|Frederick]] (for [[Western Maryland]]). There are also numerous private car, rental car, and cab services, as well as shuttles that go to and from BWI to local hotels; Baltimore and Washington and their suburbs; and [[Central Maryland|Central]] and [[Western Maryland]].\n\nBus service between BWI and the [[Greenbelt (WMATA station)|Greenbelt]] station of the [[Washington Metro]] and [[MARC Train|MARC]] [[Camden Line]] is provided by [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|WMATA's Metrobus]] on [[Greenbelt\u2013BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Express Line|Route B30]] every 70 minutes from 6am-10pm on weekdays. No weekend or holiday service is provided as it was discontinued on June 25, 2017.<ref>{{cite press release|agency=WMATA|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/upload/June25FareServiceChanges_PrintableBrochure_English.pdf|title=Be Ready for Metro Changes June 25th, 2017|date=June 25, 2017|accessdate=June 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611202107/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/upload/June25FareServiceChanges_PrintableBrochure_English.pdf|archive-date=June 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The regular fare is $7.50, and the disabled/senior citizens rate is $3.75; exact fare or the use of a WMATA SmarTrip card is required.\n\n[[BWI Rail Station]] is located about a mile from the airport terminal; the free [[BWI Marshall Airport Shuttle]] connects the train station and airport terminals. The station is served by [[Amtrak]] [[Northeast Corridor]] trains, including the partially high-speed [[Acela Express]], and the [[MARC Train|MARC]] [[MARC Train#Penn Line|Penn Line]]. Travel time by train is about twenty minutes to [[Baltimore]]'s [[Pennsylvania Station (Baltimore)|Penn Station]] and thirty-five minutes to [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] in Washington, D.C. Trains depart at least once an hour seven days a week, with departure times during rush hours and business hours being significantly more frequent.<ref>[http://mta.maryland.gov/sites/default/files/penn_Nov2011.pdf MARC Penn Line rail schedule] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111184757/http://mta.maryland.gov/sites/default/files/penn_Nov2011.pdf |date=November 11, 2011 }}. MTA Maryland. Retrieved December 15, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, BWI launched a new bicycle sharing system with the Boston-based company [[Zagster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2014-08-07/news/bs-md-bwi-zagster-20140807_1_rail-station-international-terminal-airport-travelers|title=BWI introduces bike-share pilot program for airport trail|publisher=|access-date=December 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002906/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2014-08-07/news/bs-md-bwi-zagster-20140807_1_rail-station-international-terminal-airport-travelers|archive-date=March 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Located adjacent to the [[BWI Marshall Airport (Baltimore Light Rail station)|BWI Airport Light Rail Station]], the bike sharing service connects terminal passengers to the nearby [[Airport Loop|BWI Trail]], as well as other local destinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/1136|title=Zagster Brings Pilot Bike Share Program to BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport - BWI Airport - Baltimore Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport|website=www.bwiairport.com|access-date=December 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220123442/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/1136|archive-date=December 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[File:Thomas A Dixon, Jr. Aircraft Observation Area sign.jpg|thumb|right|Thomas A Dixon, Jr. Aircraft Observation Area]]\nIn 1985, the [[BWI Business District]] was established as a way to formalize businesses and hotels operating adjacent to the airport. The district comprises two smaller districts located to the north (West Nursery Hotel District) and west (Stoney Run District) of the airport. Numerous traveler resources and employment centers are located within both districts, such as the [[BWI Rail Station]] and BWI Rental Car Facility in the Stoney Run District, and the [[BWI Business District (Baltimore Light Rail station)|BWI Business District Light Rail Station]], the [[National Security Agency|NSA]] [[Friendship Annex]], and dozens of hotel facilities in the West Nursery District.\n\nA DHS facility is located in the lower level of the main terminal, near the international arrivals area / Concourse E Baggage Claim. This facility also includes a Global Entry Enrollment Center, as well as a TSA PreCheck enrollment facility.\n\nIn the early 1990s, BWI Airport opened the Thomas A. Dixon Aircraft Observation Area at Friendship Park. The observation plaza features a playground and a terrace overlooking the southern approach to the airport's 15R-33L runway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/1190|title=BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Announces New Playground is Open - BWI Airport - Baltimore Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport|website=www.bwiairport.com|access-date=September 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922013143/http://www.bwiairport.com/en/about-bwi/press-releases/1190|archive-date=September 22, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> From this vantage point, several planes can be viewed simultaneously as they prepare for landing. The southern loop of the 13.3 mile [[Airport Loop|BWI Trail]] travels through the park, providing cyclist and pedestrian access to the park.\n\nIn addition to the Thomas A. Dixon Aircraft Observation Area, which provides spotters with views of aircraft landing on runway 33L, spotters can use one of several parking garages to view arrivals to runway 15R, with some arrivals appearing to be below the spotter.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| 3rdcoltitle = Refs | 3rdcolunsortable=yes\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air Canada Express]] | [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau]], [[Toronto Pearson International Airport|Toronto\u2013Pearson]] | <ref name=\"AirCanadaRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Flight Schedules|url=https://beta.aircanada.com/us/en/aco/home/book/routes-and-partners/flight-schedules.html?acid=beta%7Credirect%7Caircanada.com%7CNoBar|accessdate=January 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925064718/https://www.aircanada.com/us/en/aco/home/book/routes-and-partners/flight-schedules.html?acid=beta%7Credirect%7Caircanada.com%7CNoBar|archive-date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live}}<br>{{cite web|title=Flight Schedules|url=https://beta.aircanada.com/us/en/aco/home/book/routes-and-partners/flight-schedules.html?acid=beta%7Credirect%7Caircanada.com%7CNoBar|accessdate=January 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925064718/https://www.aircanada.com/us/en/aco/home/book/routes-and-partners/flight-schedules.html?acid=beta%7Credirect%7Caircanada.com%7CNoBar|archive-date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Alaska Airlines]] | [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]]<br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], [[Portland International Airport|Portland (OR)]], [[San Diego International Airport|San Diego]], [[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]] | <ref name=\"AlaskaRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Flight Timetable|url=https://m.alaskaair.com/schedule=April 7, 2020\n</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Allegiant Air]] | [[Asheville Regional Airport|Asheville]], [[Destin\u2013Fort Walton Beach Airport|Destin/Fort Walton Beach]], [[Sarasota\u2013Bradenton International Airport|Sarasota]], [[Savannah/Hilton Head International Airport|Savannah]]<br />'''Seasonal:''' [[McGhee Tyson Airport|Knoxville]], [[Tulsa International Airport|Tulsa]] | <ref name=\"AllegiantRoutes\">{{cite web|title=Allegiant Air|url=https://www.allegiantair.com|accessdate=January 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224233038/http://www.allegiantair.com/|archive-date=February 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[American Airlines]] | [[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]], [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort 